# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: theodorick-bland-congressman
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The **1st Continental Light Dragoons**, also known as **Bland's Horse**, was a mounted regiment of the Continental Army organized between 13 June and 10 September 1776 in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was made up of men from eastern and northern Virginia for service with the Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The Revolutionary Virginia Convention held in May 1776 resulted in delegates voting for a resolution to direct Virginia's delegates in Philadelphia to seek independence from the British and form a confederation of the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] They knew additional military strength was required.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Virginia Governor Patrick Henry authorized Major-Commandant Theodorick Bland to raise a volunteer battalion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Bland had participated in the expulsion of Royal Governor Dunmore.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 1st Continental Light Dragoons regiment was first authorized on 8 June 1776 in the Virginia State Troops as the 1st, 2d, 3d, 4th, 5th (Captain Henry "Light Horse Harry" Lee) and 6th Troops of Light Horse.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 25 June 1776 it mustered as the Virginia Light Horse Regiment.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was first adopted by and then accepted into the Continental Army, designated as the 1st Continental Light Dragoons on 25 November 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Six months later, when General George Washington needed cavalry to counter that of the British, the Continental Congress on November 25, 1776 requested that Virginia transfer Major Bland's Light Horse to the Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Although reluctant, Virginia acceded to the request.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Bland's Light Horse became the 1st Regiment of Continental Light Dragoons.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Each contained 3 officers, 3 corporals, a drummer, a trumpeter, and 29 privates.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Three quartermasters provided logistical support for the group.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] In March 1777 this 1st Regiment of Continental Light Dragoons — plus the three other regiments — were reorganized, resulting in a slight increase in their numbers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Each troop consisted of 32 privates, 1 armorer, 1 farrier, 1 trumpeter, 4 corporals, 1 quartermaster sergeant, a drill or an orderly sergeant, a cornet, a lieutenant, and a captain—a total of 280 men and officers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Whether any of the four regiments of Dragoons was ever at full strength is uncertain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 2nd Continental Light Dragoons hailed from Connecticut and was led by Elisha Sheldon.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It fought with distinction, whether mounted or unmounted, and at war's end had 225 men.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd Regiment—"Lady Washington's Dragoons"—was also from Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd was commanded by Lieutenant-Colonel George Baylor and seconded by Major Alexander Clough, one of George Washington's spies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 3rd was the victim of a heinous act of war when they were attacked in their billet and refused quarter in 1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 4th and final regiment drew its membership from Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, and New Jersey.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 4th suffered great losses at the Battle of Camden.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] So at the very best in 1777, there were 1120 dragoons in the Continental Army, considerably under the 3,000 troops authorized by the Continental Congress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Officers aside, there were no other mounted troops in the whole continental army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The English also had limited cavalry, fielding their 16th Queen's Lancers and 17th Regiment of Dragoons.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Light Horse Harry Lee gained national fame from his service with the 1st Continental Regiment at the Battle of Paulus Hook and in the Southern Campaign.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 31 March 1777 in General Orders, George Washington named promoted officers of the 1st Light Dragoons.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 7 April 1778 Lee's Troop was replaced by Captain Addison Lewis's Troop.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Lee's Troop was expanded into Lee's Legion, designated the 2nd Partisan Corps in 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The 1st Continental Light Dragoons were reassigned to the Southern Department on 8 November 1778, when the Corps of Continental Light Dragoons was broken up as an organization.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was officially reorganized on 1 January 1781, consisting of four mounted and two dismounted troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] It was redesignated as the 1st Legionary Corps.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] Captain Samuel Van Leer was also a member of this regiment.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] On 2 November 1782, reflecting an amalgamation that had occurred in the spring of 1780, the unit was consolidated with the 3rd Legionary Corps, maintaining five troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The new unit was designated 1st Legionary Corps.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment saw action at the Battle of Brandywine, Battle of Germantown and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/1st-continental-light-dragoons] The regiment was disbanded on November 15, 1783, at Winchester, Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was born on May 13, 1834, in Washington County, Virginia, the youngest son of Abram Fulkerson Sr.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His family took pride in their military heritage.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His grandfather, James Fulkerson, had also served as a Captain, in the Virginia Militia during the American Revolution, joining with the Overmountain Men and fighting the British at the Battle of Kings Mountain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His father, Abram Fulkerson Sr., had served during the War of 1812 as a captain of a Virginia Militia company in Colonel David Sanders' Regiment, 4th Brigade, Norfolk Division under Gen.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Porter, but by 1850 had moved to Grainger County, Tennessee, where his eldest son James L.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson died, although Abram Fulkerson Sr. moved back to Washington County, Virginia, before his death in 1859.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] The family included at least four more sons who survived to adulthood: James Lyon Fulkerson (1816–1849), Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1822–1862), Francis Marion Fulkerson (1825–1894) and Isaac Fulkerson (1831–1889).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] They also had daughters Mary Vance Fulkerson Davis (1820–1892), Harriet Jane Fulkerson Armstrong (1827–1911) and Katherine Elizabeth Fulkerson (1832–1903).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Abram Jr. graduated from the Virginia Military Institute at Lexington in 1857, where he was a student of Prof.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Thomas Jonathan Stonewall Jackson, as had been his elder brother Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1822–1862), who had served in the Mexican–American War and as a delegate to the Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1850.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] According to VMI records, Isaac Fulkerson had a reputation for being a prankster and wore an "outlandish collar" on his cadet uniform: the collar being the only part of the uniform not covered under regulations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] After graduation, he taught school in Palmyra, Virginia, then in 1860 in Rogersville, Hawkins County, Tennessee.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson entered Confederate military service in June 1861 as a Captain, having organized a company of men from Hawkins County, Tennessee, that was mustered into the 19th Tennessee Infantry Regiment as Company K (The Hawkins Boys) at Knoxville, Tennessee.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His was the first company of volunteers organized in East Tennessee, and Abram Fulkerson received a commission as the regiment's Major.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] He was wounded in the thigh and his horse shot from under him at the Battle of Shiloh.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] After recovery and the unit's reorganization, he was reassigned to the 63rd Tennessee Infantry.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Commissioned as Lieutenant Colonel of the 63rd, and President Jefferson Davis on February 12, 1864, commissioned him as a full colonel.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] In January 1862, Abram Fulkerson received a furlough and went to Clarksville, Tennessee, and married his fiancé, Selina Johnson (1832–1918) on January 28.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] They were barely married in time to escape the Union Army's advance on Clarksville.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Samuel Vance Fulkerson was killed in action leading the 37th Virginia Infantry at the Battle of Gaines Mill, the first major victory of General Robert E.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] 1829 – July 20, 1889), was a captain in the 8th Texas Cavalry (Terry's Texas Rangers).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Abram Fulkerson twice helped garrison the Cumberland Gap: first with the 19th Tennessee then with the 63rd Tennessee.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] While in the 63rd, Fulkerson was wounded twice more: in the left arm at the Battle of Chickamauga and again at the Second Battle of Petersburg, Virginia (Battle of Petersburg II), the regiment having been reassigned from the Army of Tennessee to the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] He was taken prisoner on June 17, 1864, and sent to the POW camp at Fort Delaware.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] On April 18, 1892, Fulkerson wrote an account of his capture and experiences as a prisoner.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Though none of the Immortal Six Hundred were killed by the continuing Confederate artillery fire from Fort Sumter, 14 died of dysentery.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] After Morris Island, Fulkerson was taken to Fort Pulaski and placed on starvation rations for 42 days in retaliation for Confederate prisoner abuses at Andersonville.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Crowded into the fort's cold, damp casements, the Confederates' "retaliation ration" consisted of 10 ounces of moldy cornmeal and a half pint of soured onion pickles.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] The starving men supplemented their rations with the occasional rat or stray cat.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Thirteen men died there of preventable diseases such as dysentery and scurvy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] At Fort Pulaski, the prisoners organized "The Relief Association of Fort Pulaski for Aid and Relief of the Sick and Less Fortunate Prisoners" on December 13, 1864, and Fulkerson was elected president.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Out of their sparse funds, the prisoners collected and spent eleven dollars, according to a report filed by Fulkerson on December 28, 1864.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] In March 1865 Fulkerson was returned to Fort Delaware, where he was discharged and paroled on July 25, 1865, months after General Robert E.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] While at Fort Delaware, prisoners were taken out to the badly polluted river every day and allowed to bathe and swim.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson, a very thin man with auburn hair, could float "like a cork" and would lie on his back and float out with the current for ten or fifteen minutes until the nervous guards, fearing that an escape attempt, ordered him to return to the shore.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] After Fulkerson returned home, his horse that he rode during his military service, whose official name was "Zollicoffer" (after former Congressman and early Confederate casualty Felix Zollicoffer), was returned to him.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson kept the horse for the rest of its life, but called him "Old Bob." When the horse died, former Confederates from the Bristol area assembled and conducted a military funeral for it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] In 1885, Stonewall Jackson's horse, "Little Sorrel," was brought to Bristol on a tour and Fulkerson rode it as a number of former veterans assembled to pay their respects.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] As the war ended, Fulkerson studied law, was admitted to the bar and began his legal practice in Goodson, later known as Bristol, Virginia, in 1866 with the firm of York & Fulkerson.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] As a lawyer, he was regarded as a legal giant in Bristol and it is said that he was such a gifted orator that many of the local citizens would go to court and sit in on trials just to hear him speak.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was elected and re-elected to the Virginia House of Delegates as one of two delegates representing Washington County, Virginia (part-time).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] He served from 1871 to 1875, until voters replaced both delegates.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Next he served in the State senate of Virginia 1877–1881.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Voters from Virginia's 9th congressional district elected Fulkerson as a Readjuster Democrat from to the Forty-seventh Congress (March 4, 1881 – March 3, 1883).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] He defeating incumbent James Buchanan Richmond, a lawyer and banker (and former subordinate officer to his brother Samuel in the 37th Virginia), in the Democratic primary.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson helped organize the Readjuster Party, after which he returned to the Democratic Party.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson resumed his legal practice after deciding against seeking re-election to Congress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fellow Readjuster Henry Bowen succeeded him.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Voters again elected Fulkerson to the State House of Delegates in 1888, alongside John A.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Buchanan who together replaced Daniel Trigg and Jonas S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Kelly and were in turn replaced in 1887 by John Roberts and S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] After retiring from politics, Fulkerson wrote a memoir of his captivity and published it in 1894.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was a delegate to the Democratic National (Gold) Convention in 1896.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson died in Bristol, Virginia, on December 17, 1902, at the age of 68, of complications after suffering a stroke.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Henry Clinton Wood who served as the Major of the 37th Virginia Infantry (CS) under Fulkerson's brother Samuel Vance, and for whom the town of Clintwood, Virginia, was named, served as an honorary pallbearer in the funeral.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His widow would survive for a decade, and his son Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1863–1926), although he married in Grayson, Texas, would become a Virginia lawyer and die aged 64 in Virginia Beach on July 2, 1926, and be buried in the same cemetery, East Hill Cemetery.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] VMI maintains the Fulkerson family papers in its library's archives.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] The Sons of Confederate Veterans Abram Fulkerson Camp 2104 in Greeley, Colorado, bears his name.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] His descendant third cousin, Joe Adkins, portrays Fulkerson at Civil War reenactments.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] A member of the Sons of Confederate Veterans, Adkins commands the Gen.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/abram-fulkerson] Jackson Camp 2159 in Jonesborough, Tennessee.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County was created in 1735 from parts of Prince George and Brunswick counties and was named in honor of Princess Amelia of Great Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Parts of the county were later carved out to create Prince Edward and Nottoway counties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] As of the 2020 census, the county population was 13,265.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County was created by legislative act in 1734 and 1735 from parts of Prince George and Brunswick counties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The county is named for Princess Amelia of Great Britain, daughter of King George II.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] As was customary, Amelia County was reduced by the division of territory to form newer counties as the population increased in the region; in 1754, Prince Edward County was formed from parts of Amelia County, and in 1789, Nottoway County was formed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The area was developed for plantation agriculture dependent on slave labor.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] During the Civil War, Confederate general Robert E.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Lee and his army spent April 4 and 5, 1865, at Amelia Court House before his surrender on April 9 to General Ulysses S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The last major battle of his army was fought at Sayler's Creek, on the border of Amelia and Prince Edward counties, on April 6.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia is known for its minerals, including the nation's best supply of amazonite, a green feldspar found at the Morefield mine.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] In the 19th century, spas were developed around its mineral springs, which were destinations for travelers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] In 1986 the Amelia County Fair sponsored a competition for the world's largest potato pancake (with apple sauce).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] It was constructed to raise money that year for the German American National Scholarship Fund.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The pancake weighed more than two and one-quarter tons and used four truckloads of potatoes.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 359 square miles (930 km2), of which 355 square miles (920 km2) is land and 3.3 square miles (8.5 km2) (0.9%) is water.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County lies in the Piedmont region of Virginia, known for rolling hills and small ridges that lie between the Blue Ridge Mountains and Coastal Plain of Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The county is bordered by the Appomattox River to the north and west, and Namozine Creek to the east.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County is drained by tributaries of the Appomattox.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The lowest elevation in the county is 158 feet (48 m), on Lake Chesdin on the Appomattox at the eastern extremity of the county.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The highest elevation is 525 feet (160 m), on SR 616 (S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Genito Road) at the community of Gills in the southwest corner of the county.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 13,265.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] 20.2% of residents were under the age of 18 and 21.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] For every 100 females there were 98.0 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 94.8 males age 18 and over.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 73.7% White, 19.3% Black or African American, 0.3% American Indian and Alaska Native, 0.5% Asian, 0.0% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 1.5% from some other race, and 4.8% from two or more races.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 3.2% of the population.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] 0.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 100.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] There were 5,206 households in the county, of which 28.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 22.4% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] About 23.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] There were 5,704 housing units, of which 8.7% were vacant.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Among occupied housing units, 81.8% were owner-occupied and 18.2% were renter-occupied.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.8% and the rental vacancy rate was 5.8%.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] As of the census of 2000, there were 11,400 people, 4,240 households, and 3,175 families residing in the county.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The population density was 32 people per square mile (12 people/km2).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] There were 4,609 housing units, at an average density of 13 units per square mile (5.0 units/km2).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The racial makeup of the county was 70.57% White, 28.05% Black or African American, 0.28% Native American, 0.17% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.25% from other races, and 0.67% from two or more races.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] 0.80% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] There were 4,240 households, of which 32.80% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 59.10% were married couples living together, 11.40% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.10% were non-families.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] 20.70% of all households were made up of individuals, and 8.10% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The average household size was 2.66 and the average family size was 3.07.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] For every 100 females, there were 97.30 males.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.20 males.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The median household income was $40,252, and the median family income was $47,157.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Males had a median income of $32,315, versus $23,102 for females.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] The per capita income for the county was $18,858.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] 8.40% of the population and 6.70% of families were below the poverty line.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Out of the total people living in poverty, 7.10% were under the age of 18 and 11.70% were 65 or older.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County is represented by Republican John McGuire in the Virginia Senate, Republican Lee Ware in the Virginia House of Delegates, and Republican Bob Good in the U.S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] Amelia County is served by the Amelia County Public Schools.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/amelia-county-virginia] There are no incorporated communities in Amelia County.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The movement began as a rebellion and evolved into a revolution resulting in the sovereign United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] These changes were the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd, then unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on the Fourth of July.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Throughout most of the war, the outcome appeared uncertain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] However, in 1781, a decisive victory by Washington and the Continental Army in the Siege of Yorktown led King George III and the Fox–North coalition in government to negotiate the cessation of colonial rule and the acknowledgment of American sovereignty, formalized in the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War ended in 1763.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war directly with troops, funds and material, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to ostensibly compensate for wartime costs, and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765; its "Declaration of Rights and Grievances" argued that this taxation without representation in Parliament and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions flared again following Parliament's passage of the Townshend Acts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where they killed antagonists in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the colonies-wide Sons of Liberty underground orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, intended to end self-government in Massachusetts, but instead increased American support for the revolutionary cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, twelve of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress; the Province of Georgia joined in 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, sparking the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776 they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, famously proclaiming that "all men are created equal", having then evolved from a rebellion over British rights to a revolution based on universal rights.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Congress soon after began deliberating the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years during which France ultimately entered, supporting the revolutionary cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, albeit with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, it unofficially adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Special consignees were appointed to sell the tea to bypass colonial merchants.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The act was opposed by those who resisted the taxes and also by smugglers who stood to lose business.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In every colony demonstrators warned merchants not to bring in tea that included the hated new tax.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In most instances, the consignees were forced by the Americans to resign and the tea was turned back, but Massachusetts governor Hutchinson refused to allow Boston merchants to give in to pressure.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A town meeting in Boston determined that the tea would not be landed, and ignored a demand from the governor to disperse.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On December 16, 1773, a group of men, led by Samuel Adams and dressed to evoke the appearance of Indigenous people, boarded the ships of the East India Company and dumped £10,000 worth of tea from their holds (approximately £636,000 in 2008) into Boston Harbor.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Decades later, this event became known as the Boston Tea Party and remains a significant part of American patriotic lore.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British government responded by passing four laws that came to be known as the Intolerable Acts, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The first was the Massachusetts Government Act which altered the Massachusetts charter and restricted town meetings.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The second was the Administration of Justice Act which ordered that all British soldiers to be tried were to be arraigned in Britain, not in the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The third was the Boston Port Act, which closed the port of Boston until the British had been compensated for the tea lost in the Boston Tea Party.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The fourth was the Quartering Act of 1774, which allowed royal governors to house British troops in the homes of citizens without permission of the owner.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In response, "Starting in August 1774, each time a court was slated to meet in some Massachusetts town, great numbers of angry citizens made sure it did not".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The next month Patriots issued the Suffolk Resolves and formed an alternative shadow government known as the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, which began training militia outside British-occupied Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In September 1774, the First Continental Congress convened in Pennsylvania, consisting of representatives from each colony, to serve as a vehicle for deliberation and collective action.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] During secret debates, conservative Joseph Galloway proposed the creation of a colonial Parliament that would be able to approve or disapprove acts of the British Parliament, but his idea was tabled in a vote of 6 to 5 and was subsequently removed from the record.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Congress called for a boycott beginning on December 1, 1774, of all British goods; it was enforced by new local committees authorized by the Congress that were largely built upon the earlier Committees of Correspondence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It also began coordinating Patriot resistance by militias in each colony, including many veterans who had gained military experience in the French and Indian War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] For the first time, the Patriots were armed and unified against Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] King George III declared Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion in February 1775 and the British garrison received orders to seize the rebels' weapons and arrest their leaders, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Patriots assembled a militia 15,000 strong and laid siege to Boston, occupied by 6500 British soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in Philadelphia on June 14, 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The congress was divided on the best course of action.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They authorized formation of the Continental Army, appointing George Washington as its commander-in-chief, while producing the Olive Branch Petition in which they attempted to come to an accord with King George.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The king, however, would issue a Proclamation of Rebellion in August which declared that all the states were "in rebellion" and the members of Congress were traitors.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17, 1775 was a British victory—but at a great cost: about 1,000 British casualties from a garrison of about 6,000, as compared to 500 American casualties from a much larger force.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In the winter of 1775, the Americans invaded northeastern Quebec under generals Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery, expecting to rally sympathetic colonists there.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The attack was a failure; many Americans were killed, captured, or died of smallpox.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Following the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, the Patriots had control of Massachusetts outside Boston's city limits, and the Loyalists suddenly found themselves on the defensive with no protection from the British army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In each of the Thirteen Colonies, American patriots overthrew their existing governments, closed courts, and drove out British colonial officials.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They held elected conventions and established their own legislatures, which existed outside any legal parameters established by the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] New constitutions were drawn up in each state to supersede royal charters.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They proclaimed that they were now *states*, no longer *colonies*.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On January 5, 1776, New Hampshire ratified the first state constitution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] New Jersey, South Carolina, and Virginia created their constitutions before July 4.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Rhode Island and Connecticut simply took their existing royal charters and deleted all references to the Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The new states were all committed to republicanism, with no inherited offices.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The radical provisions of Pennsylvania's constitution lasted 14 years.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1790, conservatives gained power in the state legislature, called a new constitutional convention, and rewrote the constitution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The new constitution substantially reduced universal male suffrage, gave the governor veto power and patronage appointment authority, and added an upper house with substantial wealth qualifications to the unicameral legislature.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Thomas Paine called it a constitution unworthy of America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In March 1776, aided by the fortification of Dorchester Heights with cannons recently captured at Fort Ticonderoga, the Continental Army led by George Washington forced the British to evacuate Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries now fully controlled all thirteen states and ready to declare joint independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] There still were many Loyalists, but they were no longer in control anywhere by July 1776, and all of the royal officials had fled.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In April 1776, the North Carolina Provincial Congress issued the Halifax Resolves explicitly authorizing its delegates to vote for independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] By June, nine state legislatures supported independence from Britain, and Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and New York followed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Richard Henry Lee was instructed by the Virginia legislature to propose independence, and he did so on June 7, 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Gathered at Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, later renamed Independence Hall, 56 of the nation's Founding Fathers representing the United Colonies adopted and issued to King George III the Declaration of Independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It had been drafted largely by Thomas Jefferson, and was edited and presented by the Committee of Five which was charged with authoring it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Congress struck several provisions of the Committee's draft, and then adopted it unanimously on July 4.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Declaration embodied universal rights expressed through the political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and famously proclaimed that "all men are created equal".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] What had begun as a rebellion demanding the rights of Englishmen had now evolved into a revolution to overthrow and replace the political and social order in America based on universal rights.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] With the new state constitutions and the issuance of the Declaration of Independence, each former colony began operating as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The next step was to form a union to facilitate international relations and alliances.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On November 5, 1777, the Congress approved the Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union and sent it to each state for ratification.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Congress immediately began operating under the Articles' terms, providing a structure of shared sovereignty during prosecution of the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Articles were fully ratified on March 1, 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] At that point, the Continental Congress was dissolved and a new government of the United States in Congress Assembled took its place the following day, with Samuel Huntington leading the Congress as presiding officer.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It remained a unicameral body, where each state retained one vote.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] According to British historian Jeremy Black, the British had significant advantages, including a highly trained army, the world's largest navy, and an efficient system of public finance that could easily fund the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] However, they seriously misunderstood the depth of support for the American Patriot position, misinterpreting the situation as merely a large-scale riot.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In the Siege of Boston, Washington forced the British out of the city in the spring of 1776, and neither the British nor the Loyalists controlled any significant areas.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British, however, were amassing forces at their naval base at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They returned in force in July 1776, landing in New York and defeating Washington's Continental Army toe-to-toe in August at the Battle of Brooklyn, the largest battle of the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Following that victory, and poised to take New York City, they requested a meeting with representatives from Congress to negotiate an end to hostilities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A delegation including John Adams and Benjamin Franklin met British admiral Richard Howe on Staten Island in New York Harbor on September 11 in what became known as the Staten Island Peace Conference.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Howe demanded that the Americans retract the Declaration of Independence, which they refused to do, and negotiations ended.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British then seized New York City and nearly captured Washington's army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They made the city their main political and military base of operations, holding the strategic harbor and port until November 1783.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The city became the destination for Loyalist refugees and a focal point of Washington's intelligence network.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British also took New Jersey, pushing the Continental Army into Pennsylvania.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River back into New Jersey in a surprise attack in late December 1776 and defeated the Hessian and British garrisons at Trenton and Princeton, thereby regaining control of most of New Jersey.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The victories gave an important boost to Patriots at a time when morale was flagging and enlistments were ending, and they have become iconic events of the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1777, the British sent Burgoyne's invasion force from Canada south through New York with the aim of isolating New England to the east, which the British perceived as the primary source of agitation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In anticipation of a coordinated British attack on the *de facto* revolutionary capital of Philadelphia, the Continental Congress was forced to temporarily depart Philadelphia in September for Baltimore, where they continued deliberations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Rather than move north to support Burgoyne, the British army in New York City in fact went to Philadelphia in a major case of mis-coordination, capturing it from Washington.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The invasion army from Canada was much too slow and became trapped in northern New York state.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It surrendered to the Americans after the Battles of Saratoga in October 1777.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] From early October 1777 until November 15, a siege distracted British troops at Fort Mifflin, Pennsylvania and allowed Washington time to preserve the Continental Army by safely leading his troops to harsh winter quarters at Valley Forge, some 35 miles from Philadelphia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On August 23, 1775, George III declared Americans to be traitors to the Crown if they took up arms against royal authority.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] There were thousands of British and Hessian soldiers in American hands following their surrender at the Battles of Saratoga.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Lord Germain took a hard line, but the British generals on American soil never held treason trials, and instead treated captured American soldiers as prisoners of war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The dilemma was that tens of thousands of Loyalists were under American control and American retaliation would have been easy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British built much of their strategy around using these Loyalists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British maltreated the prisoners whom they held, resulting in more American deaths in the prisons than all the American battlefield mortalities, combined.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] At the end of the war, both sides released their surviving prisoners.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The capture of a British army at Saratoga encouraged the French to formally enter the war in support of Congress, and Benjamin Franklin negotiated a permanent military alliance in early 1778; France thus became the first foreign nation to officially recognize the Declaration of Independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On February 6, 1778, the United States and France signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce and the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] William Pitt spoke out in Parliament urging Britain to make peace with the Americans and to unite against France, while British politicians who had sympathized with colonial grievances now turned against the Americans for allying with Britain's rival and enemy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Spanish and the Dutch became allies of the French in 1779 and 1780 respectively, forcing the British to fight a global war without major allies, and requiring it to slip through a combined blockade of the Atlantic.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Dutch Republic, also at war with Britain, was the next country after France to sign a treaty with the United States, on October 8, 1782.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On April 3, 1783, Ambassador Extraordinary Gustaf Philip Creutz, representing King Gustav III of Sweden, and Benjamin Franklin, signed a Treaty of Amity and Commerce with the U.S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Britain began to view the American Revolutionary War as merely one front in a wider war, and the British chose to withdraw troops from America to reinforce the British colonies in the Caribbean, which were under threat of Spanish or French invasion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] British commander Sir Henry Clinton evacuated Philadelphia and returned to New York City.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Washington intercepted him in the Battle of Monmouth Court House, the last major battle fought in the north.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] After an inconclusive engagement, the British retreated to New York City.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The northern war subsequently became a stalemate, as the focus of attention shifted to the smaller southern theater.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British Royal Navy blockaded ports and held New York City for the duration of the war, and other cities for brief periods, but failed in their effort to destroy Washington's forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British strategy now concentrated on a campaign in the southern states.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Due to a lack of regular troops at their disposal compared to the Americans, the British commanders saw the "southern strategy" as a more viable plan.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They perceived the Southern Colonies as strongly Loyalist, with a large population of recent British immigrants, and large numbers of slaves who might be tempted to run away from their Patriot masters to join the British and gain their freedom.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Beginning in late December 1778, the British captured Savannah and controlled the Georgia coastline.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In 1780, they launched a fresh invasion and took Charleston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] A significant victory at the Battle of Camden meant that royal forces soon controlled most of Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British set up a network of forts inland, hoping that the Loyalists would rally to the flag.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Not enough Loyalists turned out, however, and the British had to fight their way north into North Carolina and Virginia with a severely weakened army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Behind them, much of the territory that they had already captured dissolved into a chaotic guerrilla war, fought predominantly between bands of Loyalists and American militia, which negated many of the gains that the British had previously made.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British army under Cornwallis marched to Yorktown, Virginia, where they expected to be rescued by a British fleet.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The fleet did arrive, but so did a larger French fleet.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The French were victorious in the Battle of the Chesapeake, and the British fleet returned to New York for reinforcements, leaving Cornwallis trapped.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] In October 1781, the British surrendered their second invading army of the war under a siege by the combined French and Continental armies commanded by Washington.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Washington did not know if or when the British might reopen hostilities after Yorktown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] They still had 26,000 troops occupying New York City, Charleston, and Savannah, together with a powerful fleet.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The French army and navy departed, so the Americans were on their own in 1782–83.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The American treasury was empty, and the unpaid soldiers were growing restive, almost to the point of mutiny or possible coup d'etat.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Washington dispelled the unrest among officers of the Newburgh Conspiracy in 1783, and Congress subsequently created the promise of a five years bonus for all officers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Historians continue to debate whether the odds were long or short for American victory.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Ferling says that the odds were so long that the American victory was "almost a miracle".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, Joseph Ellis says that the odds favored the Americans, and asks whether there ever was any realistic chance for the British to win.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] He argues that this opportunity came only once, in the summer of 1776, where Admiral Howe and his brother General Howe "missed several opportunities to destroy the Continental Army ....
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Chance, luck, and even the vagaries of the weather played crucial roles." Ellis's point is that the strategic and tactical decisions of the Howes were fatally flawed because they underestimated the challenges posed by the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Ellis concludes that, once the Howe brothers failed, the opportunity "would never come again" for a British victory.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Public support for the conflict had never been strong in Britain, where many sympathized with the Americans, but now it reached a new low.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] King George wanted to fight on, but his supporters lost control of Parliament and the British launched no further offensives in America on the eastern seaboard.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] During negotiations in Paris, the American delegation discovered that France supported American independence but no territorial gains, hoping to confine the new nation to the area east of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The Americans opened direct secret negotiations with London, cutting out the French.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] British Prime Minister Lord Shelburne was in charge of the British negotiations, and he saw a chance to make the United States a valuable economic partner, facilitating trade and investment opportunities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The US obtained all the land east of the Mississippi River, including southern Canada below the Great Lakes, but Spain took control of Florida from the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] It gained fishing rights off Canadian coasts, and agreed to allow British merchants and Loyalists to recover their property.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] Prime Minister Shelburne foresaw highly profitable two-way trade between Britain and the rapidly growing United States, which did come to pass.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The blockade was lifted and American merchants were free to trade with any nation anywhere in the world.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] The British largely abandoned their Indigenous allies, who were not a party to this treaty and did not recognize it until they were defeated militarily by the United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p01] However, the British did sell them munitions and maintained forts in American territory until the Jay Treaty of 1795.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Britain's war against the Americans, the French, and the Spanish cost about £100 million.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Treasury borrowed 40 percent of the money that it needed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Britain had a sophisticated financial system based on the wealth of thousands of landowners who supported the government, together with banks and financiers in London.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In London the British had relatively little difficulty financing their war, keeping their suppliers and soldiers paid, and hiring tens of thousands of German soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In sharp contrast, Congress and the American states had no end of difficulty financing the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1775, there was at most 12 million dollars in gold in the colonies, not nearly enough to cover current transactions, let alone finance a major war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The British made the situation much worse by imposing a tight blockade on every American port, which cut off almost all trade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] One partial solution was to rely on volunteer support from militiamen and donations from patriotic citizens.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Another was to delay actual payments, pay soldiers and suppliers in depreciated currency, and promise that it would be made good after the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Indeed, the soldiers and officers were given land grants in 1783 to cover the wages that they had earned but had not been paid during the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Starting in 1776, the Congress sought to raise money by loans from wealthy individuals, promising to redeem the bonds after the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The bonds were redeemed in 1791 at face value, but the scheme raised little money because Americans had little specie, and many of the richest merchants were supporters of the Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Beginning in 1777, Congress repeatedly asked the states to provide money, but it had no system of taxation to require funds, and the states were of little help.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, Congress was making requisitions for specific supplies of corn, beef, pork, and other necessities, an inefficient system which barely kept the army alive.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Congress used four main methods to cover the cost of the war, which cost about 66 million dollars in specie (gold and silver).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Significantly, the French secretly supplied the Americans with money, gunpowder, and munitions to weaken Great Britain; the subsidies continued when France entered the war in 1778, and the French government and Paris bankers lent large sums to the American war effort.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Congress also made issues of paper money, known colloquially as "Continental Dollars", in 1775–1780 and in 1780–1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The first issue amounted to 242 million dollars.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] This paper money would supposedly be redeemed for state taxes, but the holders were eventually paid off in 1791 at the rate of one cent on the dollar.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, the paper money was so devalued that the phrase "not worth a Continental" became synonymous with valueless.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The skyrocketing inflation was a hardship on the few people who had fixed incomes, but 90 percent of the people were farmers and were not directly affected by it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Debtors benefited by paying off their debts with depreciated paper.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The greatest burden was borne by the soldiers of the Continental Army whose wages were usually paid late and depreciated in value every month, weakening their morale and adding to the hardships of their families.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The national government did not have a strong leader in financial matters until 1781, when Robert Morris was named Superintendent of Finance of the United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Morris used a French loan in 1782 to set up the private Bank of North America to finance the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He reduced the civil list, saved money by using competitive bidding for contracts, tightened accounting procedures, and demanded the national government's full share of money and supplies from the individual states.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The war ended in 1783 and was followed by a period of slow economic recovery that accompanied the end of mercantilism and the resumption and expansion of worldwide trade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The national government was still operating under the Articles of Confederation and settled the issue of the western territories, which the states ceded to Congress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] American settlers moved rapidly into those areas, with Vermont, Kentucky, and Tennessee becoming states in the 1790s.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] However, the national government had no authority to tax, no money either to pay the war debts owed to European nations and the private banks, or to pay Americans who had been given millions of dollars of promissory notes for supplies during the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Nationalists led by Washington, Alexander Hamilton, and other veterans feared that the new nation was too fragile to withstand an international war, or even the repetition of internal revolts such as the Shays's Rebellion of 1786 in Massachusetts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They convinced the Congress of the Confederation to call the Philadelphia Convention in 1787.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Convention adopted a new Constitution which provided for a republic with authority to tax and a much stronger national government in a federal framework, including an effective executive in a check-and-balance system with the judiciary and legislature.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Constitution was ratified in 1788, after a fierce debate in the states over the proposed new government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The new administration under President George Washington took office in New York in March 1789 and the new bicameral Congress of the United States was seated.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] James Madison spearheaded Congressional legislation proposing amendments to the Constitution as assurances to those cautious about federal power, guaranteeing many of the inalienable rights that formed a foundation for the revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Rhode Island was the final state to ratify the Constitution in 1790, the first ten amendments were ratified in 1791 and became known as the United States Bill of Rights.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The national debt fell into three categories after the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The first was the $12 million owed to foreigners, mostly money borrowed from France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] There was general agreement to pay the foreign debts at full value.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The national government owed $40 million and state governments owed $25 million to Americans who had sold food, horses, and supplies to the Patriot forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] There were also other debts which consisted of promissory notes issued during the war to soldiers, merchants, and farmers who accepted these payments on the premise that the new nation would create a government that would pay these debts eventually.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Americans struggled to pay off the French loans; they ceased making interest payments to France in 1785 and defaulted on installments due in 1787.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, however, they resumed regular payments on their debts to the French.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The war expenses of the individual states added up to $114 million, compared to $37 million by the central government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, Congress combined the remaining state debts with the foreign and domestic debts into one national debt totaling $80 million at the recommendation of first Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Everyone received face value for wartime certificates, so that the national honor would be sustained and the national credit established.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Accounts with the French government were settled in 1795 when James Swan, an American banker acting as agent for France, helped refinance the United States’ remaining debt to France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The American government issued bonds in the amount of the remaining debt and sold them publicly, with the proceeds going to France through Swan.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The United States no longer owed money to foreign governments, although it continued to owe money to private investors both in the United States and in Europe..
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] This allowed the young United States to place itself on a sound financial footing.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The population of the Thirteen States was not homogeneous in political views and attitudes.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Loyalties and allegiances varied widely within regions and communities and even within families, and sometimes shifted during the Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The American Enlightenment was a critical precursor of the American Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Chief among the ideas of the American Enlightenment were the concepts of natural law, natural rights, consent of the governed, self-determination, equality under the law, liberalism, republicanism, and intolerance of political corruption.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] A growing number of American colonists embraced these views and fostered an intellectual environment which led to a new sense of political and social identity.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] John Locke is often referred to as "the philosopher of the American Revolution" due to his work in the Social Contract and Natural Rights theories that underpinned the Revolution's political ideology.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Locke's *Two Treatises of Government* published in 1689 was especially influential.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He argued that all humans were created equally free, and governments therefore needed the "consent of the governed".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] This contrasted and conflicted sharply with the British system of inherited political power and hierarchy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In late eighteenth-century America, belief was still widespread in "equality by creation" and "rights by creation".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Locke's ideas on liberty influenced the political thinking of English writers such as John Trenchard, Thomas Gordon, and Benjamin Hoadly, whose political ideas in turn also had a strong influence on the American Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] His work also inspired symbols used in the American Revolution such as the "Appeal to Heaven" found on the Pine Tree Flag, which alludes to Locke's concept of the right of revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The theory of the social contract influenced the belief among many of the Founders that the right of the people to overthrow their leaders, should those leaders betray the historic rights of Englishmen, was one of the "natural rights" of man.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Americans heavily relied on Montesquieu's analysis of the wisdom of the "balanced" British Constitution (mixed government) in writing the state and national constitutions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The American interpretation of republicanism was inspired by the Whig party in Great Britain which openly criticized the corruption within the British government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Americans were increasingly embracing republican values, seeing Britain as corrupt and hostile to American interests.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Radical Whig ideology profoundly influenced colonial American political philosophy with its love of liberty and opposition to tyrannical government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The American revolutionaries associated political corruption with ostentatious luxury and inherited aristocracy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Founding Fathers were strong advocates of republican values, particularly Samuel Adams, Patrick Henry, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Paine, George Washington, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton, which required men to put civic duty ahead of their personal desires.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Men were honor bound by civic obligation to be prepared and willing to fight for the rights and liberties of their countrymen.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Protestant churches that had separated from the Church of England, called "dissenters", were the "school of democracy", in the words of historian Patricia Bonomi.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Before the Revolution, the Southern Colonies and three of the New England Colonies had official established churches: Congregational in Massachusetts Bay, Connecticut, and New Hampshire, and the Church of England in Maryland, Virginia, North-Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The colonies of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations had no officially established churches.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] John Witherspoon, who was considered a "new light" Presbyterian, wrote widely circulated sermons linking the American Revolution to the teachings of the Bible.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Throughout the colonies, dissenting Protestant ministers from the Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches preached Revolutionary themes in their sermons while most Church of England clergymen preached loyalty to the king, the titular head of the English state church.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Religious motivation for fighting tyranny transcended socioeconomic lines.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Historian Bernard Bailyn argues that the evangelicalism of the era challenged traditional notions of natural hierarchy by preaching that the Bible teaches all men are equal, and the true value of a man therefore lies in his moral behavior, not in his class.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Bailyn, on the other hand, denies that religion played such a critical role.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Alan Heimert argues that New Light anti-authoritarianism was essential to furthering democracy in colonial American society, and set the stage for a confrontation with British monarchical and aristocratic rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Historians in the early 20th century such as J.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Franklin Jameson examined the class composition of the Patriot cause, looking for evidence of a class war inside the revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] More recent historians have largely abandoned that interpretation, emphasizing instead the high level of ideological unity.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Both Loyalists and Patriots were a "mixed lot", but ideological demands always came first.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The revolution became a personal issue for the king, fueled by his growing belief that British leniency would be taken as weakness by the Americans.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He also sincerely believed that he was defending Britain's constitution against usurpers, rather than opposing patriots fighting for their natural rights.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] King George III is often accused of obstinately trying to keep Great Britain at war with the revolutionaries in America, despite the opinions of his own ministers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Later historians defend George by saying in the context of the times no king would willingly surrender such a large territory, and his conduct was far less ruthless than contemporary monarchs in Europe.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] After the surrender of a British army at Saratoga, both Parliament and the British people were largely in favor of the war; recruitment ran at high levels and although political opponents were vocal, they remained a small minority.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] With the early setbacks in America, Lord North asked to transfer power to Lord Chatham, whom he thought more capable, but George refused to do so; he suggested instead that Chatham serve as a subordinate minister in North's administration, but Chatham refused.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Lord North was allied to the "King's Friends" faction in Parliament and believed George III had the right to exercise extensive powers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In early 1778, Britain's chief rival France signed a treaty of alliance with the United States, and the confrontation soon escalated from a "rebellion" to something that has been characterized as "world war".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The French fleet was able to outrun the British naval blockade of the Mediterranean and sailed to North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The conflict now affected North America, Europe and India.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The United States and France were joined by Spain in 1779 and the Dutch Republic, while Britain had no major allies of its own, except for the Loyalist minority in America and German auxiliaries (i.e.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Lord Gower and Lord Weymouth both resigned from the government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Lord North again requested that he also be allowed to resign, but he stayed in office at George III's insistence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Opposition to the costly war was increasing, and in June 1780 contributed to disturbances in London known as the Gordon riots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] As late as the Siege of Charleston in 1780, Loyalists could still believe in their eventual victory, as British troops inflicted defeats on the Continental forces at the Battle of Camden and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In late 1781, the news of Cornwallis's surrender at the siege of Yorktown reached London; Lord North's parliamentary support ebbed away and he resigned the following year.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The king drafted an abdication notice, which was never delivered, finally accepted the defeat in North America, and authorized peace negotiations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Treaties of Paris, by which Britain recognized the sovereignty of the United States and returned Florida to Spain, were signed in 1782 and 1783 respectively.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In early 1783, George III privately conceded "America is lost!" He reflected that the former colonies had developed into Britain's "successful rivals" in commercial trade and fishing as the United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] When John Adams was appointed American Minister to London in 1785, George had become resigned to the new relationship between his country and the former colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Those who fought for independence were called "Revolutionaries", "Continentals", "Rebels", "Patriots", "Whigs", "Congress-men", or "Americans" during and after the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They included a full range of social and economic classes but were unanimous regarding the need to defend the natural rights of Americans and uphold the principles of republicanism in rejecting monarchy and aristocracy, while emphasizing civic virtue by citizens.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The signers of the Declaration of Independence were overwhelmingly—with definite exceptions—well-educated, of British stock, and of the Protestant faith.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Newspapers were strongholds of patriotism (although there were a few Loyalist papers) and printed many pamphlets, announcements, patriotic letters, and pronouncements.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] According to historian Robert Calhoon, 40 to 45 percent of the white population in the Thirteen Colonies supported the Patriots' cause, 15 to 20 percent supported the Loyalists, and the remainder were neutral or kept a low profile.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Mark Lender concludes that ordinary people became insurgents against the British because they held a sense of rights which the British were violating, rights that stressed local autonomy, fair dealing, and government by consent.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They were highly sensitive to the issue of tyranny, which they saw manifested in the British response to the Boston Tea Party.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The arrival in Boston of the British Army heightened their sense of violated rights, leading to rage and demands for revenge.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They had faith that God was on their side.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Patriots viewed independence as a means to gain freedom from British oppression and initially to reassert their rights on par with subjects in Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Most yeomen farmers, craftsmen, and small merchants joined the Patriot cause to demand more political equality.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They were especially successful in Pennsylvania but less so in New England, where John Adams attacked Thomas Paine's *Common Sense* for the "absurd democratical notions" that it proposed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Thomas Paine published his pamphlet *Common Sense* in January 1776, after the Revolution had started.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] It was widely distributed and often read aloud in taverns, contributing significantly to concurrently spreading the ideas of republicanism and liberalism, bolstering enthusiasm for separation from Great Britain, and encouraging recruitment for the Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Paine presented the Revolution as the solution for Americans alarmed by the threat of tyranny.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The consensus of scholars is that about 15 to 20 percent of the white population remained loyal to the British Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Those who actively supported the king were known at the time as "Loyalists", "Tories", or "King's men".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Loyalists never controlled territory unless the British Army occupied it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They were typically older, less willing to break with old loyalties, and often connected to the Church of England; they included many established merchants with strong business connections throughout the Empire, as well as royal officials such as Thomas Hutchinson of Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In the mid-20th century, historian Leonard Woods Labaree identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative, opposite to the characteristics of the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists tended to feel that resistance to the Crown was morally wrong, while the Patriots thought that morality was on their side.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and tarring and feathering.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists wanted to take a centrist position and resisted the Patriots' demand to declare their opposition to the Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Numerous Loyalists had maintained strong and long-standing relations with Britain, especially merchants in port cities such as New York and Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists felt that independence was bound to come eventually, but they were fearful that revolution might lead to anarchy, tyranny, or mob rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In contrast, the prevailing attitude among Patriots was a desire to seize the initiative.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Labaree also contended that Loyalists were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] There were "tens of thousands" of Black Loyalists, enslaved African Americans who escaped to British lines and supported Britain's cause via several means.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many of them died from disease, but the survivors were evacuated by the British to their remaining colonies in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The revolution could divide families, such as William Franklin, son of Benjamin Franklin and royal governor of the Province of New Jersey who remained loyal to the Crown throughout the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Recent immigrants who had not been fully Americanized were also inclined to support the King.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] After the war, the great majority of the half-million Loyalists remained in America and resumed normal lives.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Some became prominent American leaders, such as Samuel Seabury.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Approximately 46,000 Loyalists relocated to Canada; others moved to Britain (7,000), Florida, or the West Indies (9,000).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The exiles represented approximately two percent of the total population of the colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Nearly all Black Loyalists left for Nova Scotia, Florida, or England, where they could remain free.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists who left the South in 1783 took thousands of enslaved persons with them as they fled to the British West Indies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] A minority of uncertain size tried to stay neutral in the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Most kept a low profile, but the Quakers were the most important group to speak out for neutrality, especially in Pennsylvania.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Quakers continued to do business with the British even after the war began, and they were accused of supporting British rule, "contrivers and authors of seditious publications" critical of the revolutionary cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Most Quakers remained neutral, although a sizeable number participated to some degree.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Women contributed to the American Revolution in many ways and were involved on both sides.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Formal politics did not include women, but ordinary domestic behaviors became charged with political significance as Patriot women confronted a war which permeated all aspects of political, civil, and domestic life.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They participated by boycotting British goods, spying on the British, following armies as they marched, washing, cooking, and mending for soldiers, delivering secret messages, and even fighting disguised as men in a few cases, such as Deborah Samson.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Mercy Otis Warren held meetings in her house and cleverly attacked Loyalists with her creative plays and histories.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many women also acted as nurses and helpers, tending to the soldiers' wounds and buying and selling goods for them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Some of these camp followers even participated in combat, such as Madam John Turchin who led her husband's regiment into battle.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Above all, women continued the agricultural work at home to feed their families and the armies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They maintained their families during their husbands' absences and sometimes after their deaths.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] American women were integral to the success of the boycott of British goods, as the boycotted items were largely household articles such as tea and cloth.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Women had to return to knitting goods and to spinning and weaving their own cloth—skills that had fallen into disuse.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1769, the women of Boston produced 40,000 skeins of yarn, and 180 women in Middletown, Massachusetts wove 20,522 yards (18,765 m) of cloth.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many women gathered food, money, clothes, and other supplies during the war to help the soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] A woman's loyalty to her husband could become an open political act, especially for women in America committed to men who remained loyal to the King.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Legal divorce, usually rare, was granted to Patriot women whose husbands supported the King.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In early 1776, France set up a major program of aid to the Americans, and the Spanish secretly added funds.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Each country spent one million "livres tournaises" to buy munitions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] A dummy corporation run by Pierre Beaumarchais concealed their activities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots obtained some munitions from the Dutch Republic as well, through the French and Spanish ports in the West Indies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Heavy expenditures and a weak taxation system pushed France toward bankruptcy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1777, Charles François Adrien le Paulmier, Chevalier d'Annemours, acting as a secret agent for France, made sure General George Washington was privy to his mission.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He followed Congress around for the next two years, reporting what he observed back to France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Treaty of Alliance between the French and the Americans followed in 1778, which led to more French money, matériel and troops being sent to the United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Spain did not officially recognize the United States, but it was a French ally and it separately declared war on Britain on June 21, 1779.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Bernardo de Gálvez, general of the Spanish forces in New Spain bordering the Americans, also served as governor of Louisiana.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He led an expedition of colonial troops to capture Florida from the British and to keep open a vital conduit for supplies going to the Americans.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Ethnic Germans served on both sides of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] As George III was also the Elector of Hanover, many supported the Loyalist cause and served as allies of the Kingdom of Great Britain; most notably rented auxiliary troops from German states such as the Landgraviate of Hessen-Kassel.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots tended to represent such troops as mercenaries in propaganda against the British Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Even American historians followed suit, in spite of Colonial-era jurists drawing a distinction between auxiliaries and mercenaries, with auxiliaries serving their prince when sent to the aid of another prince, and mercenaries serving a foreign prince as individuals.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] By this distinction the troops which served in the American Revolution were auxiliaries.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Other German individuals came to assist the American revolutionaries, most notably Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben, who served as a general in the Continental Army and is credited with professionalizing that force, but most Germans who served were already colonists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Von Steuben's native Prussia joined the League of Armed Neutrality, and King Frederick II of Prussia was well appreciated in the United States for his support early in the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] He expressed interest in opening trade with the United States and bypassing English ports, and allowed an American agent to buy arms in Prussia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Frederick predicted American success, and promised to recognize the United States and American diplomats once France did the same.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Prussia also interfered in the recruiting efforts of Russia and neighboring German states when they raised armies to send to the Americas, and Frederick II forbade enlistment for the American war within Prussia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] All Prussian roads were denied to troops from Anhalt-Zerbst, which delayed reinforcements that Howe had hoped to receive during the winter of 1777–1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] However, when the War of the Bavarian Succession (1778–1779) erupted, Frederick II became much more cautious with Prussian/British relations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] U.S. ships were denied access to Prussian ports, and Frederick refused to officially recognize the United States until they had signed the Treaty of Paris.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Even after the war, Frederick II predicted that the United States was too large to operate as a republic, and that it would soon rejoin the British Empire with representatives in Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Most Indigenous people rejected pleas that they remain neutral and instead supported the British Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The great majority of the ~200,000 indigenous people east of the Mississippi distrusted the Americans and supported the British cause, hoping to forestall continued expansion of settlement into their territories.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Those tribes closely involved in trade tended to side with the Patriots, although political factors were important as well.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Some tried to remain neutral, seeing little value in joining what they perceived to be a "white man's war", and fearing reprisals from whichever side they opposed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The British did have other indigenous allies, particularly in the regions of southwest Quebec on the Patriot's frontier.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The British provided arms to Indigenous people who were led by Loyalists in war parties to raid frontier settlements from the Carolinas to New York.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] These war parties killed many settlers on the frontier, especially in western Pennsylvania and New York's Mohawk Valley.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1776, Cherokee war parties attacked American settlers all along the southern Quebec frontier of the uplands throughout the Washington District, North Carolina (now Tennessee) and the Kentucky wilderness area.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Chickamauga Cherokee under Tsiyu Gansini (*also* Dragging Canoe) allied themselves closely with the British, and fought on for an additional decade after the Treaty of Paris was signed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They launched raids with roughly 200 warriors, as seen in the Cherokee–American wars; they could not mobilize enough forces to invade settler areas without the help of allies, most often the Creek.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Joseph Brant (*also* Thayendanegea), from the powerful Mohawk tribe of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy, was the most prominent Indigenous leader against the Patriot forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1778 and 1780, he led 300 Iroquois warriors and 100 white Loyalists in multiple attacks on small frontier settlements in New York and Pennsylvania, killing many settlers and destroying villages, crops, and food stockpiles.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In 1779, the Continental Army forced the hostile Indigenous people out of upstate New York when Washington sent an army under John Sullivan which destroyed 40 evacuated Iroquois villages in central and western New York.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The Battle of Newtown proved decisive, as the Patriots had an advantage of three-to-one, and it ended significant resistance; there was little combat otherwise.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Facing starvation and homeless for the winter, the Iroquois that allied with the British fled to Canada.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] At the peace conference following the war, the British ceded lands which they did not really control, without consultation with their Indigenous allies that inhabited them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They transferred control to the United States of all the land south of the Great Lakes east of the Mississippi and north of Florida.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The existence of slavery in the American colonies had attracted criticism from both sides of the Atlantic as many could not reconcile the existence of the institution with the egalitarian ideals espoused by leaders of the Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The English writer Samuel Johnson wrote "how is it we hear the loudest yelps for liberty among the drivers of the Negroes?" in a text opposing the grievances of the colonists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Crispus Attucks, of mixed racial heritage, was one of the five people killed in the Boston Massacre in 1770 and is considered the first American casualty for the cause of independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Free Blacks in the New England Colonies and Middle Colonies in the North as well as Southern Colonies fought on both sides of the War, but the majority fought for the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Gary Nash reports that there were about 9,000 Black veteran Patriots, counting the Continental Army and Navy, state militia units, privateers, wagoneers in the Army, servants to officers, and spies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The effects of the war were more dramatic in the South.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Tens of thousands of enslaved persons escaped to British lines throughout the South, causing dramatic losses to slaveholders and disrupting cultivation and harvesting of crops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] For instance, South Carolina was estimated to have lost about 25,000 enslaved persons to flight, migration, or death which amounted to a third of its enslaved population.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] As noted by the historian Karen Cook Bell, during the Revolutionary War roughly one-third of all the escaped enslaved were women, even though prior to 1775 nearly 87% had been men.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] During the war, British commanders attempted to weaken the Patriots by issuing proclamations of freedom to their enslaved.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] In the November 1775 document known as Dunmore's Proclamation Virginia royal governor, Lord Dunmore recruited Black men for British military service with the promise of freedom, protection for their families, and land grants.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Hundreds of Black men responded and were formed into the Royal Ethiopian Regiment.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Colonists, primarily Southern Patriots, were deeply angered by Dunmore's proclamation, which spread through all of the Thirteen Colonies and threatened to upturn the existing American racial hierarchy; it also played a major role in Southern support for American independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Accusations that the British were encouraging slave rebellions were prominent features of Patriot propaganda, with Jefferson even accusing George III in the 27 colonial grievances of having "excited domestic Insurrections among us".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation expanded the promise of freedom for Black men who enlisted in the British military to all the colonies in rebellion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] At the conclusion of the war, British forces gave transportation to 10,000 of the formerly enslaved when they evacuated Savannah and Charles Town, carrying through on their promise.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] They evacuated and resettled more than 3,000 Black Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia, Upper Canada, and Lower Canada.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Others sailed with the British to England or were resettled as freedmen in the West Indies of the Caribbean.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] But the enslaved carried to the Caribbean under control of Loyalist masters generally remained enslaved until the British abolition of slavery in its colonies in 1833–1838.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] More than 1,200 of the Black Loyalists of Nova Scotia later resettled in the British colony of Sierra Leone in Africa, where they became leaders of the Krio ethnic group of Freetown and the later national government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Many of their descendants still live in Sierra Leone, as well as other African countries.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Despite the turmoil of the period, African-Americans contributed to the foundation of an American national identity during the Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p02] Phyllis Wheatley, an African American poet, popularized the image of Columbia to represent America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] After the Revolution, genuinely democratic politics became possible in the former American colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The rights of the people were incorporated into state constitutions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Concepts of liberty, consent of the governed, individual rights, equality and due process under the law, and intolerance of corruption became incorporated as core values of liberal republicanism.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The new United States government was empowered to undertake its own project of territorial expansion and settler colonialism.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The greatest challenge to the old order in Europe was the challenge to inherited political power and the democratic idea that government rests on the consent of the governed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Losing the war and the Thirteen Colonies was a shock to Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The war revealed the limitations of Britain's fiscal-military state when they discovered that they suddenly faced powerful enemies with no allies, and they were dependent on extended and vulnerable transatlantic lines of communication.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The defeat heightened dissension and escalated political antagonism to the king's ministers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The king went so far as to draft letters of abdication, although they were never delivered.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Inside Parliament, the primary concern changed from fears of an over-mighty monarch to the issues of representation, parliamentary reform, and government retrenchment.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Unable to accept loss of the war and the colonies as possibly due to anything else but widespread institutional corruption, reformers sought to root it out, and the result was a crisis from 1776 to 1783.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The crisis ended after 1784 confidence in the British constitution was restored during the administration of Prime Minister William Pitt.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution ended an age—an age of monarchy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] And, it began a new age—an age of freedom.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] As a result of the growing wave started by the Revolution, there are now more people around the world living in freedom than ever before, both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of the world's population.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Interpretations vary concerning the effect of the Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Historians such as Bernard Bailyn, Gordon Wood, and Edmund Morgan view it as a unique and radical event which produced deep changes and had a profound effect on world affairs, such as an increasing belief in the principles of the Enlightenment.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] These were demonstrated by a leadership and government that espoused protection of natural rights, and a system of laws chosen by the people.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] John Murrin, by contrast, argues that the definition of "the people" at that time was mostly restricted to free men who passed a property qualification.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The first shot of the American Revolution at the Battle of Lexington and Concord is referred to as the "shot heard 'round the world".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution was the first of the Atlantic Revolutions: followed most notably by the French Revolution, the Haitian Revolution, and the Latin American wars of independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Aftershocks contributed to rebellions in Ireland, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Netherlands.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Constitution, drafted shortly after independence, remains the world's oldest written constitution, and has been emulated by other countries, in some cases verbatim.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Some historians and scholars argue that the subsequent wave of independence and revolutionary movements has contributed to the continued expansion of democratic government; 144 countries, representing two-third of the world's population, are full or partially democracies of some form.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution had a strong, immediate influence in Great Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Many British and Irish Whigs in Parliament spoke glowingly in favor of the American cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In Ireland, the Protestant minority who controlled Ireland demanded self-rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Under the leadership of Henry Grattan, the Irish Patriot Party forced the reversal of mercantilist prohibitions against trade with other British colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The King and his cabinet in London could not risk another rebellion, and so made a series of concessions to the Patriot faction in Dublin.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Armed volunteer units of the *Protestant Ascendancy* were set up ostensibly to protect against an invasion from France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] As had been in colonial America, so too in Ireland now the King no longer had a monopoly of lethal force.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] By 1798, the Irish were ready for a republican uprising.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] For many Europeans, such as the Marquis de Lafayette, who later were active during the era of the French Revolution, the American case along with the Dutch Revolt (end of the 16th century) and the 17th century English Civil War, was among the examples of overthrowing an old regime.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The American Declaration of Independence influenced the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1789.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The spirit of the Declaration of Independence led to laws ending slavery in all the Northern states and the Northwest Territory, with New Jersey the last in 1804.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] States such as New Jersey and New York adopted gradual emancipation, which kept some people as slaves for more than two decades longer.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] During the revolution, the contradiction between the Patriots' professed ideals of liberty and the institution of slavery generated increased scrutiny of the latter.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] As early as 1764, the Boston Patriot leader James Otis, Jr. declared that all men, "white or black", were "by the law of nature" born free.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Anti-slavery calls became more common in the early 1770s.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In 1773, Benjamin Rush, the future signer of the Declaration of Independence, called on "advocates for American liberty" to oppose slavery.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Slavery became an issue that had to be addressed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In the late 1760s and early 1770s, several colonies, including Massachusetts and Virginia, attempted to restrict the slave trade, but were prevented from doing so by royally appointed governors.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In 1774, as part of a broader non-importation movement aimed at Britain, the Continental Congress called on all the colonies to ban the importation of enslaved people, and the colonies passed acts doing so.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In the first two decades after the American Revolution, state legislatures and individuals took actions to free the enslaved, in part based on Revolutionary ideals.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Northern states passed new constitutions that contained language about equal rights or specifically abolished slavery; some states, such as New York and New Jersey, where slavery was more widespread, passed laws by the end of the 18th century to abolish slavery by a gradual method.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] By 1804, all the northern states had passed laws outlawing slavery, either immediately or over time.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] However, enslavers could grant freedom to individuals they enslaved.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Numerous slaveholders who freed their enslaved cited Revolutionary ideals in their documents; others freed their enslaved as a reward for service.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Records also suggest that some slaveholders were freeing their own mixed-race children, born to enslaved mothers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The number of free Blacks as a proportion of the Black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, slavery continued in the South, where it was protected as a "peculiar institution", setting the stage for future sectional conflict between North and South over the issue.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Thousands of free Blacks in the northern states fought in the state militias and Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In the south, both sides offered freedom to slaves who would perform military service.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Roughly 20,000 enslaved persons fought in the American Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] While women were entering a period in which they found themselves gaining more identity within society, it was clear that they were still very much considered under men as their role in society remained being a good wife and mother.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Having a woman who was dressed well for her role as a good wife and mother as well as fitting the social role, was a symbol of not only status, but a family devoted to the republic.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] As they continued to nurture social and political partnerships, their role in enabling the success of the revolution emphasized their changing role in society – leading to the post-revolutionary reconstruction of gender ideology.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In addition, the democratic ideals of the Revolution inspired changes in the roles of women.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Patriot women married to Loyalists who left the state could get a divorce and obtain control of the ex-husband's property.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] As discussions rose regarding the rights of man post Revolutionary war, women began pushing a debate for the rights of women as well.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Mary Wollstonecraft pioneered the discussion regarding women's rights, and push those like Abigail Adams to begin expressing the desire to want a larger place in society.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Wollstonecraft was an English writer, philosopher, and advocate for women's rights, and would publish the *Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1792) – challenging the idea that rights should only be granted to men.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Her radical ideas would give ground to the conversation in allowing women to be bearers of rights alongside men – that while the rights of man were taking on a new meaning post-revolutionary America, it was time for the rights of women too.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Inspired by the radical feminism in her work, women in the early republic would change their views on marriage, education, participation in public life, and autonomy – pushing them to lay the groundwork for the later women's suffrage movement, education opportunities, property rights, and more.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] However, this new sense of independence and dignity did not come with ease, as a gender hierarchy would continue to bind what it meant for women to have rights during the post-revolutionary era.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Women in the early republic had many limitations – they could not vote, hold political office, earn fair wages, lacked opportunities for higher education and certain professions, and most importantly, own property independently of their husbands.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] In addition, they held little legal powers in subjects such as divorce, property rights, and child custody.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] A central legal concept that reinforced these restrictions was *coverture*, a central legal doctrine that limited women's lives in all aspects – making a woman's legal identity a part of their husband's.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The early national period of America would continue to struggle with the concept of rights and equality.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Tens of thousands of Loyalists left the United States following the war; Philip Ranlet estimates 20,000, while Maya Jasanoff estimates as many as 70,000.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Some migrated to Britain, but the great majority received land and subsidies for resettlement in British colonies in North America, especially Quebec (concentrating in the Eastern Townships), Prince Edward Island, and Nova Scotia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Britain created the colonies of Upper Canada (Ontario) and New Brunswick expressly for their benefit, and the Crown awarded land to Loyalists as compensation for losses in the United States.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, approximately eighty-five percent of the Loyalists stayed in the United States as American citizens, and some of the exiles later returned to the U.S.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Patrick Henry spoke of the issue of allowing Loyalists to return as such: "Shall we, who have laid the proud British lion at our feet, be frightened of its whelps?" His actions helped secure return of the Loyalists to American soil.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution has a central place in the American memory as the story of the nation's founding.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] It is covered in the schools, memorialized by two national holidays, Washington's Birthday in February and Independence Day in July, and commemorated in innumerable monuments.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] George Washington's estate at Mount Vernon was one of the first national pilgrimages for tourists and attracted 10,000 visitors a year by the 1850s.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution became a matter of contention in the 1850s in the debates leading to the American Civil War (1861–1865), as spokesmen of both the Northern United States and the Southern United States claimed that their region was the true custodian of the legacy of 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The United States Bicentennial in 1976 came a year after the American withdrawal from the Vietnam War, and speakers stressed the themes of renewal and rebirth based on a restoration of traditional values.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] Today, more than 100 battlefields and historic sites of the American Revolution are protected and maintained by the government.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolution-p03] The National Park Service alone manages and maintains more than 50 battlefield parks and many other sites such as Independence Hall that are related to the Revolution.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was fought in North America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The war's outcome seemed uncertain for most of the war, but Washington and the Continental Army's decisive victory in the Siege of Yorktown in 1781 led King George III and the Kingdom of Great Britain to negotiate an end to the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1783, in the Treaty of Paris, the British monarchy acknowledged the independence of the Thirteen Colonies, leading to the establishment of the United States as an independent and sovereign nation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1763, after the British Empire gained dominance in North America following its victory over the French in the Seven Years' War, tensions and disputes began escalating between the British and the Thirteen Colonies, especially following passage of the Stamp and Townshend Acts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Army responded by seeking to occupy Boston militarily, leading to the Boston Massacre on March 5, 1770.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In mid-1774, with tensions escalating even further between the British Army and the colonies, the British Parliament imposed the Intolerable Acts, an attempt to disarm Americans, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord in April 1775, the first battles of the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In June 1775, the Second Continental Congress voted to incorporate colonial-based Patriot militias into a central military, the Continental Army, and unanimously appointed Washington its commander-in-chief.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Two months later, in August 1775, George III declared the colonies to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1776, the Second Continental Congress formalized the war, passing the Lee Resolution on July 2, and, two days later, unanimously adopting the Declaration of Independence, on July 4.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In March 1776, in an early win for the newly-formed Continental Army under Washington's command, following a successful siege of Boston, the Continental Army successfully drove the British Army out of Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] British commander in chief William Howe responded by launching the New York and New Jersey campaign, which resulted in Howe's capture of New York City in November.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Washington responded by clandestinely crossing the Delaware River and winning small but significant victories at Trenton and Princeton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the summer of 1777, as Howe was poised to capture Philadelphia, the Continental Congress fled to Baltimore.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In October 1777, a separate northern British force under the command of John Burgoyne was forced to surrender at Saratoga in an American victory that proved crucial in convincing France and Spain that an independent United States was a viable possibility.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] France signed a commercial agreement with the revolutionaires, followed by a Treaty of Alliance in February 1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1779, the Sullivan Expedition undertook a scorched earth campaign against British-allied factions of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois).
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Native American raids on the American frontier, however, continued to be a problem.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Also, in 1779, Spain allied with France against Great Britain in the Treaty of Aranjuez, though Spain did not formally ally with the Americans.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Howe's replacement Henry Clinton intended to take the war against the Americans into the Southern Colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Despite some initial success, British General Cornwallis was besieged by a Franco-American army in Yorktown, Virginia, in September and October 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French navy cut off Cornwallis's escape and he was forced to surrender in October.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British wars with France and Spain continued for another two years, but fighting largely ceased in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the Treaty of Paris, signed on September 3, 1783, Great Britain acknowledged the sovereignty and independence of the United States, bringing the American Revolutionary War to an end.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Treaties of Versailles resolved Great Britain's conflicts with France and Spain, and forced Great Britain to cede Tobago, Senegal, and small territories in India to France, and Menorca, West Florida, and East Florida to Spain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French and Indian War, part of the wider global conflict known as the Seven Years' War, ended with the 1763 Peace of Paris, which expelled France from their possessions in New France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 was designed to refocus colonial expansion north into Nova Scotia and south into Florida, with the Mississippi River as the dividing line between British and Spanish possessions in America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Settlement was tightly restricted beyond the 1763 limits, and claims west of this line, including by Virginia and Massachusetts, were rescinded.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Virginia and others deprived of rights to western lands, the colonial legislatures agreed on the boundaries but disagreed on where to set them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many settlers resented the restrictions entirely, and enforcement required permanent garrisons along the frontier, which led to increasingly bitter disputes over who should pay for them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The huge debt incurred by the Seven Years' War and demands from British taxpayers for cuts in government expenditure meant Parliament expected the colonies to fund their own defense.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The 1763 to 1765 Grenville ministry instructed the Royal Navy to cease trading smuggled goods and enforce customs duties levied in American ports.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The most important was the 1733 Molasses Act; routinely ignored before 1763, it had a significant economic impact since 85% of New England rum exports were manufactured from imported molasses.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] These measures were followed by the Sugar Act and Stamp Act, which imposed additional taxes on the colonies to pay for defending the western frontier.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The taxes proved highly burdensome, particularly for the poorer classes, and quickly became a source of discontent.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1765, the Whigs formed the First Rockingham ministry, which repealed the Stamp Act and reduced tax on foreign molasses to help the New England economy, but re-asserted Parliamentary authority in the Declaratory Act.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, this did little to end the discontent; in 1768, a riot started in Boston when the authorities seized the sloop *Liberty* on suspicion of smuggling.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated in March 1770 when British troops fired on rock-throwing civilians, killing five in what became known as the Boston Massacre.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Massacre coincided with the partial repeal of the Townshend Acts by the Tory-based North Ministry.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] North insisted on retaining duty on tea to enshrine Parliament's right to tax the colonies; the amount was minor, but ignored the fact it was that very principle Americans found objectionable.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In April 1772, colonialists staged the first American tax revolt against British royal authority in Weare, New Hampshire, later referred to as the Pine Tree Riot.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This would inspire the design of the Pine Tree Flag.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated following the destruction of a customs vessel in the June 1772 Gaspee Affair, then came to a head in 1773.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] A banking crisis led to the near-collapse of the East India Company, which dominated the British economy; to support it, Parliament passed the Tea Act, giving it a trading monopoly in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Since most American tea was smuggled by the Dutch, the act was opposed by those who managed the illegal trade, while being seen as another attempt to impose the principle of taxation by Parliament.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In December 1773, a group called the Sons of Liberty disguised as Mohawks dumped crates of tea into Boston Harbor, an event later known as the Boston Tea Party.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Parliament responded by passing the so-called Intolerable Acts, aimed specifically at Massachusetts, although many colonists and members of the Whig opposition considered them a threat to liberty in general.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This increased sympathy for the Patriot cause locally, in the British Parliament, and in the London press.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Throughout the 18th century, the elected lower houses in the colonial legislatures gradually wrested power from their governors.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Dominated by smaller landowners and merchants, these assemblies now established ad-hoc provincial legislatures, effectively replacing royal control.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Georgia, twelve colonies sent representatives to the First Continental Congress to agree on a unified response to the crisis.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many of the delegates feared that a boycott would result in war and sent a Petition to the King calling for the repeal of the Intolerable Acts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After some debate, on September 17, 1774, Congress endorsed the Massachusetts Suffolk Resolves and on October 20 passed the Continental Association, which instituted economic sanctions and a boycott of goods against Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] While denying its authority over internal American affairs, a faction led by James Duane and future Loyalist Joseph Galloway insisted Congress recognize Parliament's right to regulate colonial trade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Expecting concessions by the North administration, Congress authorized the colonial legislatures to enforce the boycott; this succeeded in reducing British imports by 97% from 1774 to 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, on February 9 Parliament declared Massachusetts to be in rebellion and instituted a blockade of the colony.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July, the Restraining Acts limited colonial trade with the British West Indies and Britain and barred New England ships from the Newfoundland cod fisheries.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The tension led to a scramble for control of militia stores, which each assembly was legally obliged to maintain for defense.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On April 19, a British attempt to secure the Concord arsenal culminated in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, which began the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After the Patriot victory at Concord, moderates in Congress led by John Dickinson drafted the Olive Branch Petition, offering to accept royal authority in return for George III mediating in the dispute.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, since the petition was immediately followed by the Declaration of the Causes and Necessity of Taking Up Arms, Colonial Secretary Lord Dartmouth viewed the offer as insincere and refused to present the petition to the king.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Although constitutionally correct, since the monarch could not oppose his own government, it disappointed those Americans who hoped he would mediate in the dispute, while the hostility of his language annoyed even Loyalist members of Congress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Combined with the Proclamation of Rebellion, issued on August 23 in response to the Battle at Bunker Hill, it ended hopes of a peaceful settlement.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Backed by the Whigs, Parliament initially rejected the imposition of coercive measures by 170 votes, fearing an aggressive policy would drive the Americans towards independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, by the end of 1774 the collapse of British authority meant both Lord North and George III were convinced war was inevitable.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After Boston, Gage halted operations and awaited reinforcements; the Irish Parliament approved the recruitment of new regiments, while allowing Catholics to enlist for the first time.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Britain also signed a series of treaties with German states to supply additional troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Within a year, it had an army of over 32,000 men in America, the largest ever sent outside Europe at the time.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The employment of German soldiers against people viewed as British citizens was opposed by many in Parliament and by the colonial assemblies; combined with the lack of activity by Gage, opposition to the use of foreign troops allowed the Patriots to take control of the legislatures.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Support for independence was boosted by Thomas Paine's pamphlet *Common Sense*, which was published on January 10, 1776, and argued for American self-government and was widely reprinted.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] To draft the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress appointed the Committee of Five: Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Roger Sherman, and Robert Livingston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The declaration was written almost exclusively by Jefferson.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Identifying inhabitants of the Thirteen Colonies as "one people", the declaration simultaneously dissolved political links with Britain, while including a long list of alleged violations of "English rights" committed by George III.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This is also one of the first times that the colonies were referred to as "United States", rather than the more common United Colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On July 2, Congress voted for independence and published the declaration on July 4.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At this point, the revolution ceased to be an internal dispute over trade and tax policies between the Thirteen Colonies and Great Britain, becoming a civil war, with each state represented in Congress engaged in a struggle with Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was also a civil war between American Patriots and American Loyalists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Patriots generally supported independence from Britain and a new national union in Congress, while Loyalists remained aligned with British rule.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Estimates of numbers vary, one suggestion being the population as a whole was split evenly between committed Patriots, committed Loyalists, and those who were indifferent.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Others calculate the split as 40% Patriot, 40% neutral, 20% Loyalist, but with considerable regional variations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At the onset of the war, the Second Continental Congress realized defeating Britain required foreign alliances and intelligence-gathering.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Committee of Secret Correspondence was formed for "the sole purpose of corresponding with our friends in Great Britain and other parts of the world".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] From 1775 to 1776, the committee shared information and built alliances through secret correspondence, as well as employing secret agents in Europe to gather intelligence, conduct undercover operations, analyze foreign publications, and initiate Patriot propaganda campaigns.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Paine served as secretary, while Benjamin Franklin and Silas Deane, sent to France, Britain's longtime rival, to recruit military engineers, were instrumental in securing French aid in Paris.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 14, 1775, Sir Thomas Gage, Commander-in-Chief, North America and Governor of Massachusetts, received orders to take action against the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He decided to destroy militia ordnance stored at Concord, Massachusetts, and capture John Hancock and Samuel Adams, who were considered the principal instigators of the rebellion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The operation was to begin around midnight on April 19, in the hope of completing it before the American Patriots could respond.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Paul Revere learned of the plan and notified Captain Parker, commander of the Concord militia, who prepared to resist.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The first action of the war, commonly referred to as the shot heard round the world, was a brief skirmish at Lexington, followed by the full-scale Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British troops suffered around 300 casualties before withdrawing to Boston, which was then besieged by the militia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In May 1775, 4,500 British reinforcements arrived under Generals William Howe, John Burgoyne, and Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 17, they seized the Charlestown Peninsula at the Battle of Bunker Hill, a frontal assault in which they suffered over 1,000 casualties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Dismayed at the costly attack which had gained them little, Gage appealed to London for a larger army, but instead was replaced as commander by Howe.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 14, 1775, Congress took control of Patriot forces outside Boston, and Congressional leader John Adams nominated Washington as commander-in-chief of the newly formed Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 16, Hancock officially proclaimed him "General and Commander in Chief of the army of the United Colonies." He assumed command on July 3, preferring to fortify Dorchester Heights outside Boston rather than assaulting it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early March 1776, Colonel Henry Knox arrived with heavy artillery acquired in the Capture of Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under cover of darkness, on March 5, Washington placed these on Dorchester Heights, from where they could fire on the town and British ships in Boston Harbor.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Fearing another Bunker Hill, Howe evacuated the city on March 17 without further loss and sailed to Halifax, Nova Scotia, while Washington moved south to New York City.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Beginning in August 1775, American privateers raided towns in Nova Scotia, including Saint John, Charlottetown, and Yarmouth.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1776, John Paul Jones and Jonathan Eddy attacked Canso and Fort Cumberland respectively.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British officials in Quebec began negotiating with the Iroquois for their support, while US envoys urged them to remain neutral.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Aware of Native American leanings toward the British and fearing an Anglo-Indian attack from Canada, Congress authorized a second invasion in April 1775.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After the defeat at the Battle of Quebec on December 31, the Americans maintained a loose blockade of the city until they retreated on May 6, 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second defeat at Trois-Rivières on June 8 ended operations in Quebec.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British pursuit was initially blocked by American naval vessels on Lake Champlain until victory at Valcour Island on October 11 forced the Americans to withdraw to Fort Ticonderoga, while in December an uprising in Nova Scotia sponsored by Massachusetts was defeated at Fort Cumberland.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These failures impacted public support for the Patriot cause, and aggressive anti-Loyalist policies in the New England colonies alienated the Canadians.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Virginia, Dunmore's Proclamation on November 7, 1775, promised freedom to any slaves who fled their Patriot masters and agreed to fight for the Crown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British forces were defeated at Great Bridge on December 9 and took refuge on British ships anchored near Norfolk.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the Third Virginia Convention refused to disband its militia or accept martial law, Lord Dunmore ordered the Burning of Norfolk on January 1, 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The siege of Savage's Old Fields began on November 19 in South Carolina between Loyalist and Patriot militias, and the Loyalists were subsequently driven out of the colony in the Snow Campaign.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalists were recruited in North Carolina to reassert British rule in the South, but they were decisively defeated in the Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British expedition sent to reconquer South Carolina launched an attack on Charleston in the Battle of Sullivan's Island on June 28, 1776, but it failed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A shortage of gunpowder led Congress to authorize a naval expedition against the Bahamas to secure ordnance stored there.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On March 3, 1776, an American squadron under the command of Esek Hopkins landed at the east end of Nassau and encountered minimal resistance at Fort Montagu.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins' troops then marched on Fort Nassau.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins had promised governor Montfort Browne and the civilian inhabitants that their lives and property would not be in any danger if they offered no resistance; they complied.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins captured large stores of powder and other munitions that was so great he had to impress an extra ship in the harbor to transport the supplies back home, when he departed on March 17.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A month later, after a brief skirmish with HMS *Glasgow*, they returned to New London, Connecticut, the base for American naval operations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After regrouping at Halifax in Nova Scotia, Howe set sail for New York in June 1776 and began landing troops on Staten Island near the entrance to New York Harbor on July 2.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans rejected Howe's informal attempt to negotiate peace on July 30; Washington knew that an attack on the city was imminent and realized that he needed advance information to deal with disciplined British regular troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 12, 1776, Patriot Thomas Knowlton was ordered to form an elite group for reconnaissance and secret missions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowlton's Rangers, which included Nathan Hale, became the Army's first intelligence unit.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Washington was driven off Long Island, he soon realized that he would need to professionalize military intelligence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With aid from Benjamin Tallmadge, Washington launched the six-man Culper spy ring.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The efforts of Washington and the Culper Spy Ring substantially increased the effective allocation and deployment of Continental regiments in the field.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Throughout the war, Washington spent more than 10 percent of his total military funds on military intelligence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington split the Continental Army into positions on Manhattan and across the East River in western Long Island.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 27 at the Battle of Long Island, Howe outflanked Washington and forced him back to Brooklyn Heights, but he did not attempt to encircle Washington's forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Through the night of August 28, Knox bombarded the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowing they were up against overwhelming odds, Washington ordered the assembly of a war council on August 29; all agreed to retreat to Manhattan.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington quickly had his troops assembled and ferried them across the East River to Manhattan on flat-bottomed freight boats without any losses in men or ordnance, leaving General Thomas Mifflin's regiments as a rearguard.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe met with a delegation from the Second Continental Congress at the September Staten Island Peace Conference, but it failed to conclude peace, largely because the British delegates only had the authority to offer pardons and could not recognize independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On September 15, Howe seized control of New York City when the British landed at Kip's Bay and unsuccessfully engaged the Americans at the Battle of Harlem Heights the following day.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On October 18, Howe failed to encircle the Americans at the Battle of Pell's Point, and the Americans withdrew.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe declined to close with Washington's army on October 28 at the Battle of White Plains and instead attacked a hill that was of no strategic value.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington's retreat isolated his remaining forces and the British captured Fort Washington on November 16.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British victory there amounted to Washington's most disastrous defeat with the loss of 3,000 prisoners.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The remaining American regiments on Long Island fell back four days later.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Henry Clinton wanted to pursue Washington's disorganized army, but he was first required to commit 6,000 troops to capture Newport, Rhode Island, to secure the Loyalist port.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Charles Cornwallis pursued Washington, but Howe ordered him to halt.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The outlook following the defeat at Fort Washington appeared bleak for the American cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The reduced Continental Army had dwindled to fewer than 5,000 men and was reduced further when enlistments expired at the end of the year.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Popular support wavered, and morale declined.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 20, 1776, the Continental Congress abandoned the revolutionary capital of Philadelphia and moved to Baltimore, where it remained until February 27, 1777.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist activity surged in the wake of the American defeat, especially in New York state.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In London, news of the victorious Long Island campaign was well received with festivities held in the capital.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Strategic deficiencies among Patriot forces were evident: Washington divided a numerically weaker army in the face of a stronger one, his inexperienced staff misread the military situation, and American troops fled in the face of enemy fire.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The successes led to predictions that the British could win within a year.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British established winter quarters in the New York City area and anticipated renewed campaigning the following spring.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the night of December 25–26, 1776, Washington crossed the Delaware River, leading a column of Continental Army troops from today's Bucks County, Pennsylvania, to today's Mercer County, New Jersey, in a logistically challenging and dangerous operation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Hessians were involved in numerous clashes with small bands of Patriots and were often aroused by false alarms at night in the weeks before the actual Battle of Trenton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By Christmas they were tired, while a heavy snowstorm led their commander, Colonel Johann Rall, to assume no significant attack would occur.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At daybreak on the 26th, the American Patriots surprised and overwhelmed Rall and his troops, who lost over 20 killed including Rall, while 900 prisoners, German cannons and supplies were captured.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Battle of Trenton restored the American army's morale, reinvigorated the Patriot cause, and dispelled their fear of what they regarded as Hessian "mercenaries".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British attempt to retake Trenton was repulsed at Assunpink Creek on January 2; during the night, Washington outmaneuvered Cornwallis, then defeated his rearguard in the Battle of Princeton the following day.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two victories helped convince the French that the Americans were worthy military allies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After his success at Princeton, Washington entered winter quarters at Morristown, New Jersey, where he remained until May and received Congressional direction to inoculate all Patriot troops against smallpox.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With the exception of a minor skirmishing between the two armies which continued until March, Howe made no attempt to attack the Americans.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1776 campaign demonstrated that regaining New England would be a prolonged affair, which led to a change in British strategy to isolating the north by taking control of the Hudson River, allowing them to focus on the south where Loyalist support was believed to be substantial.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In December 1776, Howe wrote to the Colonial Secretary Lord Germain, proposing a limited offensive against Philadelphia, while a second force moved down the Hudson from Canada.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne supplied several alternatives, all of which gave him responsibility for the offensive, with Howe remaining on the defensive.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The option selected required him to lead the main force south from Montreal down the Hudson Valley, while a detachment under Barry St.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two would meet at Albany, leaving Howe to decide whether to join them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reasonable in principle, this did not account for the logistical difficulties involved and Burgoyne erroneously assumed Howe would remain on the defensive; Germain's failure to make this clear meant he opted to attack Philadelphia instead.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With a mixed force of British regulars, professional German soldiers and Canadian militia Burgoyne set out on June 14, 1777, and captured Fort Ticonderoga on July 5.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As General Horatio Gates retreated, his troops blocked roads, destroyed bridges, dammed streams, and stripped the area of food.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This slowed Burgoyne's progress and forced him to send out large foraging expeditions; one of more than 700 British troops were captured at the Battle of Bennington on August 16.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] St Leger moved east and besieged Fort Stanwix; despite defeating an American relief force at the Battle of Oriskany on August 6, St.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Leger was abandoned by his Indian allies and withdrew to Quebec on August 22.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Now isolated and outnumbered by Gates, Burgoyne continued onto Albany rather than retreating to Fort Ticonderoga, reaching Saratoga on September 13.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He asked Clinton for support while constructing defenses around the town.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale among his troops rapidly declined, and an unsuccessful attempt to break past Gates at the Battle of Freeman Farms on September 19 resulted in 600 British casualties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Clinton advised he could not reach them, Burgoyne's subordinates advised retreat; a reconnaissance in force on October 7 was repulsed by Gates at the Battle of Bemis Heights, forcing them back into Saratoga with heavy losses.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By October 11, all hope of British escape had vanished; persistent rain reduced the camp to a "squalid hell" and supplies were dangerously low.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne capitulated on October 17; around 6,222 soldiers, including German forces commanded by General Friedrich Adolf Riedesel, surrendered their arms before being taken to Boston, where they were to be transported to England.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After securing additional supplies, Howe made another attempt on Philadelphia by landing his troops in Chesapeake Bay on August 24.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He now compounded failure to support Burgoyne by missing repeated opportunities to destroy his opponent: despite defeating Washington at the Battle of Brandywine on September 11, he then allowed him to withdraw in good order.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After dispersing an American detachment at Paoli on September 20, Cornwallis occupied Philadelphia on September 26, with the main force of 9,000 under Howe based just to the north at Germantown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington attacked them on October 4, but was repulsed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To prevent Howe's forces in Philadelphia being resupplied by sea, the Patriots erected Fort Mifflin and nearby Fort Mercer on the east and west banks of the Delaware respectively, and placed obstacles in the river south of the city.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was supported by a small flotilla of Continental Navy ships on the Delaware, supplemented by the Pennsylvania State Navy, commanded by John Hazelwood.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempt by the Royal Navy to take the forts in the October 20 to 22 Battle of Red Bank failed; a second attack captured Fort Mifflin on November 16, while Fort Mercer was abandoned two days later when Cornwallis breached the walls.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] His supply lines secured, Howe tried to tempt Washington into giving battle, but after inconclusive skirmishing at the Battle of White Marsh from December 5 to 8, he withdrew to Philadelphia for the winter.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 19, the Americans followed suit and entered winter quarters at Valley Forge.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As Washington's domestic opponents contrasted his lack of battlefield success with Gates' victory at Saratoga, foreign observers such as Frederick the Great were equally impressed with Washington's command at Germantown, which demonstrated resilience and determination.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Over the winter, poor conditions, supply problems and low morale resulted in 2,000 deaths, with another 3,000 unfit for duty due to lack of shoes.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Baron Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben took the opportunity to introduce Prussian Army drill and infantry tactics to "model companies" in each Continental Army regiment, who then instructed their home units.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite Valley Forge being only twenty miles away, Howe made no effort to attack their camp, an action some critics argue could have ended the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Like his predecessors, French foreign minister Vergennes considered the 1763 Peace a national humiliation and viewed the war as an opportunity to weaken Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He initially avoided open conflict, but allowed American ships to take on cargoes in French ports, a technical violation of neutrality.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Vergennes persuaded Louis XVI to secretly fund a government front company to purchase munitions for the Patriots, carried in neutral Dutch ships and imported through Sint Eustatius in the Caribbean.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Many Americans opposed a French alliance, fearing to "exchange one tyranny for another", but this changed after a series of military setbacks in early 1776.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As France had nothing to gain from the colonies reconciling with Britain, Congress had three choices: making peace on British terms, continuing the struggle on their own, or proclaiming independence, guaranteed by France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Declaration of Independence had wide public support, over 20% of Congressmen voted against an alliance with France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Congress agreed to the treaty with reluctance and as the war moved in their favor increasingly lost interest in it.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Silas Deane was sent to Paris to begin negotiations with Vergennes, whose key objectives were replacing Britain as the United States' primary commercial and military partner while securing the French West Indies from American expansion.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These islands were extremely valuable; in 1772, the value of sugar and coffee produced by Saint-Domingue on its own exceeded that of all American exports combined.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Talks progressed slowly until October 1777, when British defeat at Saratoga and their apparent willingness to negotiate peace convinced Vergennes only a permanent alliance could prevent the "disaster" of Anglo-American rapprochement.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Assurances of formal French support allowed Congress to reject the Carlisle Peace Commission and insist on nothing short of complete independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On February 6, 1778, France and the United States signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce regulating trade between the two countries, followed by a defensive military alliance against Britain, the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In return for French guarantees of American independence, Congress undertook to defend their interests in the West Indies, while both sides agreed not to make a separate peace; conflict over these provisions would lead to the 1798 to 1800 Quasi-War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Charles III of Spain was invited to join on the same terms but refused, largely due to concerns over the impact of the Revolution on Spanish colonies in the Americas.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Spain had complained on multiple occasions about encroachment by American settlers into Louisiana, a problem that could only get worse once the United States replaced Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although Spain ultimately made important contributions to American success, in the Treaty of Aranjuez, Charles agreed only to support France's war with Britain outside America, in return for help in recovering Gibraltar, Menorca and Spanish Florida.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The terms were confidential since several conflicted with American aims; for example, the French claimed exclusive control of the Newfoundland cod fisheries, a non-negotiable for colonies like Massachusetts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] One less well-known impact of this agreement was the abiding American distrust of 'foreign entanglements'; the US would not sign another treaty with France until their NATO agreement of 1949.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was because the US had agreed not to make peace without France, while Aranjuez committed France to keep fighting until Spain recovered Gibraltar, effectively making it a condition of US independence without the knowledge of Congress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To encourage French participation in the struggle for independence, the US representative in Paris, Silas Deane, promised promotion and command positions to any French officer who joined the Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This included Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette, whom Congress via Dean appointed a major general, on July 31, 1777.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the war started, Britain tried to borrow the Dutch-based Scots Brigade for service in America, but pro-Patriot sentiment led the States General to refuse.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Republic was no longer a major power, prior to 1774 they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, a conflict that proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British government failed to take into account the strength of the American merchant marine and support from European countries, which allowed the colonies to import munitions and continue trading with relative impunity.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] While well aware of this, the North administration delayed placing the Royal Navy on a war footing for cost reasons; this prevented the institution of an effective blockade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Traditional British policy was to employ European land-based allies to divert the opposition; in 1778, they were diplomatically isolated and faced war on multiple fronts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, George III had given up on subduing America while Britain had a European war to fight.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He did not welcome war with France, but he held the British victories over France in the Seven Years' War as a reason to believe in ultimate victory over France.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Britain subsequently changed its focus into the Caribbean theater, and diverted major military resources away from America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At the end of 1777, Howe resigned and was replaced by Sir Henry Clinton on May 24, 1778; with French entry into the war, he was ordered to consolidate his forces in New York.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 18, the British departed Philadelphia with the reinvigorated Americans in pursuit; the Battle of Monmouth on June 28 was inconclusive but boosted Patriot morale.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That midnight, the newly installed Clinton continued his retreat to New York.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A French naval force under Admiral Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing was sent to assist Washington; deciding New York was too formidable a target, in August they launched a combined attack on Newport, with General John Sullivan commanding land forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The resulting Battle of Rhode Island was indecisive; badly damaged by a storm, the French withdrew to avoid risking their ships.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Further activity was limited to British raids on Chestnut Neck and Little Egg Harbor in October.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1779, the Americans captured British positions at Stony Point and Paulus Hook.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton unsuccessfully tried to tempt Washington into a decisive engagement by sending General William Tryon to raid Connecticut.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, a large American naval operation, the Penobscot Expedition, attempted to retake Maine but was defeated.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Persistent raids by British-allied tribes in New York and Pennsylvania led to the punitive Sullivan Expedition from July to September 1779.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, 5,000 British-allied tribes of Iroquois fled to Canada where, supplied and supported by the British, they continued their raids.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] During the winter of 1779–1780, the Continental Army suffered greater hardships than at Valley Forge.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale was poor, public support fell away, the Continental dollar was virtually worthless, the army was plagued with supply problems, desertion was common, and mutinies occurred in the Pennsylvania Line and New Jersey Line regiments over the conditions.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1780, Clinton sent 6,000 men under Wilhelm von Knyphausen to retake New Jersey, but they were halted by local militia at the Battle of Connecticut Farms; although the Americans withdrew, Knyphausen felt he was not strong enough to engage Washington's main force and retreated.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second attempt two weeks later ended in a British defeat at the Battle of Springfield, effectively ending their ambitions in New Jersey.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, Washington appointed Benedict Arnold commander of West Point; his attempt to betray the fort to the British failed due to incompetent planning, and the plot was revealed when his British contact John André was captured and executed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Arnold escaped to New York and switched sides, an action justified in a pamphlet addressed "To the Inhabitants of America"; the Patriots condemned his betrayal, while he found himself almost as unpopular with the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern Strategy was developed by Lord Germain, based on input from London-based Loyalists, including Joseph Galloway.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] They argued that it made no sense to fight the Patriots in the north where they were strongest, while the New England economy was reliant on trade with Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the other hand, duties on tobacco made the South far more profitable for Britain, while local support meant securing it required small numbers of regular troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Victory would leave a truncated United States facing British possessions to the south, north, and west; with the Atlantic seaboard controlled by the Royal Navy, Congress would be forced to agree to terms.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, assumptions about the level of Loyalist support proved wildly optimistic.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Germain ordered Augustine Prevost, the British commander in East Florida, to advance into Georgia in December 1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lieutenant-Colonel Archibald Campbell, an experienced officer, captured Savannah on December 29, 1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He recruited a Loyalist militia of nearly 1,100, many of whom allegedly joined only after Campbell threatened to confiscate their property.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Poor motivation and training made them unreliable troops, as demonstrated in their defeat by Patriot militia at the Battle of Kettle Creek on February 14, 1779, although this was offset by British victory at Brier Creek on March 3.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1779, Prevost launched an abortive assault on Charleston, before retreating to Savannah, an operation notorious for widespread looting by British troops that enraged both Loyalists and Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In October, a joint French and American operation under d'Estaing and General Benjamin Lincoln failed to recapture Savannah.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Prevost was replaced by Lord Cornwallis, who assumed responsibility for Germain's strategy; he soon realized estimates of Loyalist support were considerably over-stated, and he needed far more regular forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reinforced by Clinton, Cornwallis's troops captured Charleston in May 1780, inflicting the most serious Patriot defeat of the war; over 5,000 prisoners were taken and the Continental Army in the south effectively destroyed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 29, Lieutenant-Colonel Banastre Tarleton's mainly Loyalist force routed a Continental Army force nearly three times its size under Colonel Abraham Buford at the Battle of Waxhaws.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The battle is controversial for allegations of a massacre, which were later used as a recruiting tool by the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton returned to New York, leaving Cornwallis to oversee the south; despite their success, the two men left barely on speaking terms.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern strategy depended on local support, but this was undermined by a series of coercive measures.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Previously, captured Patriots were sent home after swearing not to take up arms against the king; they were now required to fight their former comrades, while the confiscation of Patriot-owned plantations led formerly neutral "grandees" to side with them.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Skirmishes at Williamson's Plantation, Cedar Springs, Rocky Mount, and Hanging Rock signaled widespread resistance to the new oaths throughout South Carolina.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1780, Congress appointed Gates commander in the south; he was defeated at the Battle of Camden on August 16, leaving Cornwallis free to enter North Carolina.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite battlefield success, the British could not control the countryside and Patriot attacks continued; before moving north, Cornwallis sent Loyalist militia under Major Patrick Ferguson to cover his left flank, leaving their forces too far apart to provide mutual support.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early October, Ferguson was defeated at the Battle of Kings Mountain, dispersing organized Loyalist resistance in the region.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite this, Cornwallis continued into North Carolina hoping for Loyalist support, while Washington replaced Gates with General Nathanael Greene in December 1780.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene divided his army, leading his main force southeast pursued by Cornwallis; a detachment was sent southwest under Daniel Morgan, who defeated Tarleton's British Legion at Cowpens on January 17, 1781, nearly eliminating it as a fighting force.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now held the initiative in the south, with the exception of a raid on Richmond led by Benedict Arnold in January 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene led Cornwallis on a series of countermarches around North Carolina; by early March, the British were exhausted and short of supplies and Greene felt strong enough to fight the Battle of Guilford Court House on March 15.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although victorious, Cornwallis suffered heavy casualties and retreated to Wilmington, North Carolina, seeking supplies and reinforcements.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now controlled most of the Carolinas and Georgia outside the coastal areas; after a minor reversal at the Battle of Hobkirk's Hill, they captured Fort Balfour on April 13 and recaptured Fort Watson and Fort Motte on April 15.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 6, Brigadier General Andrew Pickens captured Augusta, leaving the British in Georgia confined to Charleston and Savannah.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The assumption Loyalists would do most of the fighting left the British short of troops and battlefield victories came at the cost of losses they could not replace.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite halting Greene's advance at the Battle of Eutaw Springs on September 8, Cornwallis withdrew to Charleston with little to show for his campaign.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] From the beginning of the war, Bernardo de Gálvez, the Governor of Spanish Louisiana, allowed the Americans to import supplies and munitions into New Orleans, then ship them to Pittsburgh.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided an alternative transportation route for the Continental Army, bypassing the British blockade of the Atlantic Coast.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In February 1778, an expedition of militia to destroy British military supplies in settlements along the Cuyahoga River was halted by adverse weather.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later in the year, a second campaign was undertaken to seize the Illinois Country from the British.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Virginia militia, *Canadien* settlers, and Indian allies commanded by Colonel George Rogers Clark captured Kaskaskia on July 4 and then secured Vincennes, though Vincennes was recaptured by Quebec Governor Henry Hamilton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish-aligned fur trader Francis Vigo, an American sympathizer, alerted Clark to the threat posed to his control of the west by Hamilton's position and in early 1779, the Virginians counter-attacked in the siege of Fort Vincennes and took Hamilton prisoner.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clark secured western British Quebec as the American Northwest Territory in the Treaty of Paris as the Revolutionary War came to an end.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Spain joined France's war against Britain in the Anglo-French War in 1779, their treaty specifically excluded Spanish military action in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later that year, however, Gálvez initiated offensive operations against British outposts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] First, he cleared British garrisons in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, Fort Bute, and Natchez, Mississippi, and captured five forts.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In doing so, Gálvez opened navigation on the Mississippi River north to the American settlement in Pittsburgh.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 25, 1780, British Colonel Henry Bird invaded Kentucky as part of a wider operation to clear American resistance from Quebec to the Gulf Coast.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Their advance on New Orleans was repelled by Spanish Governor Gálvez's offensive on Mobile.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Simultaneous British attacks were repulsed on St.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Louis by the Spanish Lieutenant Governor de Leyba, and on the Virginia County courthouse in Cahokia, Illinois, by Lieutenant Colonel Clark.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British initiative under Bird from Detroit was ended at the rumored approach of Clark.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The scale of violence in the Licking River Valley, was extreme "even for frontier standards." It led to English and German settlements, who joined Clark's militia when the British and their hired German soldiers withdrew to the Great Lakes.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans responded with a major offensive along the Mad River in August which met with some success in the Battle of Piqua but did not end Indian raids.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] French soldier Augustin de La Balme led a Canadian militia in an attempt to capture Detroit, but they dispersed when Miami natives led by Little Turtle attacked the encamped settlers on November 5.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The war in the west stalemated with the British garrison sitting in Detroit and the Virginians expanding westward settlements north of the Ohio River in the face of British-allied Indian resistance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1781, Galvez and Pollock campaigned east along the Gulf Coast to secure West Florida, including British-held Mobile and Pensacola.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish operations impaired the British supply of armaments to British Indian allies, which effectively suspended a military alliance to attack settlers between the Mississippi River and the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1782, large scale retaliations between settlers and Native Americans in the region included the Gnadenhutten massacre and the Crawford expedition.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1782 Battle of Blue Licks was one of the last major engagements of the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] News of the treaty between Great Britain and the United States arrived late that year.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By this time, about 7% of Kentucky settlers had been killed in battles against Native Americans, contrasted with 1% of the population killed in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lingering resentments led to continued fighting in the west after the war officially ended.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton spent most of 1781 based in New York City; he failed to construct a coherent operational strategy, partly due to his difficult relationship with Admiral Marriot Arbuthnot.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Charleston, Cornwallis independently developed an aggressive plan for a campaign in Virginia, which he hoped would isolate Greene's army in the Carolinas and cause the collapse of Patriot resistance in the South.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This strategy was approved by Lord Germain in London, but neither informed Clinton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington and Rochambeau discussed their options: Washington wanted to attack the British in New York, and Rochambeau wanted to attack them in Virginia, where Cornwallis's forces were less established.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington eventually gave way, and Lafayette took a combined Franco-American force into Virginia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton misinterpreted his movements as preparations for an attack on New York and instructed Cornwallis to establish a fortified sea base, where the Royal Navy could evacuate British troops to help defend New York.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Lafayette entered Virginia, Cornwallis complied with Clinton's orders and withdrew to Yorktown, where he constructed strong defenses and awaited evacuation.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An agreement by the Spanish Navy to defend the French West Indies allowed Admiral François Joseph Paul de Grasse to relocate to the Atlantic seaboard, a move Arbuthnot did not anticipate.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided Lafayette naval support, while the failure of previous combined operations at Newport and Savannah meant their coordination was planned more carefully.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite repeated urging from his subordinates, Cornwallis made no attempt to engage Lafayette before he could establish siege lines.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Expecting to be withdrawn within a few days, he also abandoned the outer defenses, which were promptly occupied by the besiegers and hastened British defeat.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 31, a Royal Navy fleet under Thomas Graves left New York for Yorktown.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After landing troops and munitions for the besiegers on August 30, de Grasse remained in Chesapeake Bay and intercepted him on September 5; although the Battle of the Chesapeake was indecisive in terms of losses, Graves was forced to retreat, leaving Cornwallis isolated.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempted breakout over the York River at Gloucester Point failed due to bad weather.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under heavy bombardment with dwindling supplies, on October 16 Cornwallis sent emissaries to General Washington to negotiate surrender; after twelve hours of negotiations, the terms of surrender were finalized the following day.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Responsibility for defeat was the subject of fierce public debate between Cornwallis, Clinton, and Germain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton ultimately took most of the blame and spent the rest of his life in relative obscurity.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Subsequent to Yorktown, American forces were assigned to supervise the armistice between Washington and Clinton made to facilitate British departure following the January 1782 law of Parliament forbidding any further British offensive action in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British-American negotiations in Paris led to signed preliminary agreements in November 1782, which acknowledged US independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The enacted Congressional war objective, a British withdrawal from North America and cession of these regions to the US, was completed in stages in East Coast cities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In the US South, Generals Greene and Wayne observed the British removing their troops from Charleston on December 14, 1782.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist provincial militias of whites and free Blacks and Loyalists with slaves were transported to Nova Scotia and the British West Indies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Native American allies of the British and some freed Blacks were left to escape unaided through the American lines.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 9, 1783, Washington issued orders that "all acts of hostility" were to cease immediately.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That same day, by arrangement with Washington, Carleton issued a similar order to British troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As directed by a Congressional resolution of May 26, 1783, all non-commissioned officers and enlisted were furloughed "to their homes" until the "definitive treaty of peace", when they would be automatically discharged.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The US armies were directly disbanded in the field as of Washington's General Orders on June 2, 1783.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Once the Treaty of Paris was signed with Britain on September 3, 1783, Washington resigned as commander-in-chief of the Continental Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The last British occupation of New York City ended on November 25, 1783, with the departure of Clinton's replacement, General Sir Guy Carleton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To win their insurrection, Washington and the Continental Army needed to outlast the British will to fight.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To restore British America, the British had to defeat the Continental Army quickly and compel the Second Continental Congress to retract its claim to self-governance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Mays of The Citadel identifies three separate types of warfare during the Revolutionary War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first was a colonial conflict in which objections to imperial trade regulation were as significant as taxation policy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The second was a civil war between American Patriots, American Loyalists, and those who preferred to remain neutral.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Particularly in the south, many battles were fought between Patriots and Loyalists with no British involvement, leading to divisions that continued after independence was achieved.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The third element was a global war between France, Spain, the Dutch Republic, and Britain, with America serving as one of several different war theaters.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After entering the Revolutionary War in 1778, France provided the Americans money, weapons, soldiers, and naval assistance, while French troops fought under US command in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Spain did not formally join the war in America, they provided access to the Mississippi River and captured British possessions on the Gulf of Mexico that denied bases to the Royal Navy, retook Menorca and besieged Gibraltar in Europe.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Dutch Republic was no longer a major power prior to 1774, they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits by shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, and the conflict proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Americans stood to benefit if the Continental Army remained intact and the armed conflict became a protracted war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British supply lines were long, replacement of troops difficult, and the war was expensive.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Colonial populations were largely prosperous and depended on local production for food and supplies rather than on imports from Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The thirteen colonies were spread across most of North American Atlantic seaboard, stretching 1,000 miles.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Most colonial farms were remote from the seaports, and control of four or five major ports did not give Britain control over American inland areas.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Each state had established internal distribution systems.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Motivation was also a major asset: each colonial capital had its own newspapers and printers, and the Patriots enjoyed more popular support than the Loyalists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Britain hoped that the Loyalists would do much of the fighting, but found that the Loyalists did not engage as significantly as they had hoped.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the Revolutionary War began, the Second Continental Congress lacked a professional army or navy.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, each of the colonies had a long-established system of local militia, which were combat-tested in support of British regulars in the French and Indian War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The colonial state legislatures independently funded and controlled their local militias.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Militiamen were lightly armed, had little training, and usually did not have uniforms.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Their units served for only a few weeks or months at a time and lacked the training and discipline of more experienced soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Local county militias were reluctant to travel far from home and were unavailable for extended operations.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To compensate for this, the Continental Congress established a regular force known as the Continental Army on June 14, 1775, which proved to be the origin of the modern United States Army, and appointed Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, it suffered significantly from the lack of an effective training program and from largely inexperienced officers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] One of Washington's most successful general officer recruits was Steuben, a veteran of the Prussian general staff who wrote the Revolutionary War Drill Manual.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Both sides used partisan warfare, but the state militias effectively suppressed Loyalist activity when British regulars were not in the area.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington designed the overall military strategy in cooperation with Congress, established the principle of civilian supremacy in military affairs, personally recruited his senior officer corps, and kept the states focused on a common goal.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington initially employed the inexperienced officers and untrained troops in Fabian strategies rather than risk frontal assaults against Britain's professional forces.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over the course of the war, Washington lost more battles than he won, but he never surrendered his troops and maintained a fighting force in the face of British field armies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] By prevailing European standards, the armies in America were relatively small, limited by lack of supplies and logistics.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British were constrained by the logistical difficulty of transporting troops across the Atlantic and their dependence on local supplies.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington never directly commanded more than 17,000 men, and the combined Franco-American army in the decisive American victory at Yorktown was only about 19,000.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of 1776, Patriot forces consisted of 20,000 men, with two-thirds in the Continental Army and the other third in the state militias.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 250,000 American men served as regulars or as militia for the revolutionary cause during the war, but there were never more than 90,000 men under arms at any time.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On the whole, American officers never equaled their British opponents in tactics and maneuvers, and they lost most of the pitched battles.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The great successes at Boston (1776), Saratoga (1777), and Yorktown (1781) were won by trapping the British far from base with a greater number of troops.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After 1778, Washington's army was transformed into a more disciplined and effective force, mostly as a product of Baron von Steuben's military training.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the Battle of Monmouth, Washington came to realize that saving entire towns was not necessary, but preserving his army and keeping the revolutionary spirit alive was more important.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Continental Congress was responsible for the war effort and provided supplies to the troops, Washington took it upon himself to pressure Congress and the state legislatures to provide the essentials of war; there was never nearly enough.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress evolved in its committee oversight and established the Board of War, which included members of the military.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Because the Board of War was also a committee ensnared with its own internal procedures, Congress also created the post of Secretary of War, appointing Major General Benjamin Lincoln to the position in February 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with Lincoln to coordinate civilian and military authorities and took charge of training and supplying the army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] During the first summer of the war, Washington began outfitting schooners and other small seagoing vessels to prey on ships supplying the British in Boston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Second Continental Congress established the Continental Navy on October 13, 1775, and appointed Esek Hopkins as its first commander; for most of the war, the Continental Navy included only a handful of small frigates and sloops, supported by privateers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On November 10, 1775, Congress authorized the creation of the Continental Marines, which ultimately evolved into the United States Marine Corps.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Paul Jones became the first American naval hero when he captured HMS *Drake* on April 24, 1778, the first victory for any American military vessel in British waters.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The last such victory was by the frigate USS *Alliance*, commanded by Captain John Barry.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On March 10, 1783, the *Alliance* outgunned HMS *Sybil* in a 45-minute duel while escorting Spanish gold from Havana to the Congress in Philadelphia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After Yorktown, all US Navy ships were sold or given away; it was the first time in America's history that it had no fighting forces on the high seas.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress primarily commissioned privateers to reduce costs and to take advantage of the large proportion of colonial sailors found in the British Empire.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In total, they included 1,700 ships that successfully captured 2,283 enemy ships to damage the British effort and to enrich themselves with the proceeds from the sale of cargo and the ship itself.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 55,000 sailors served aboard American privateers during the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of the war, the Americans had no major international allies, since most nation-states waited to see how the conflict unfolded.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over time, the Continental Army established its military credibility.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The decisive American victory at Saratoga convinced France, which was already a long-time rival of Britain, to offer the Americans the Treaty of Amity and Commerce.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The two nations also agreed to a defensive Treaty of Alliance to protect their trade and also guaranteed American independence from Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To engage the United States as a French ally militarily, the treaty was conditioned on Britain initiating a war on France to stop it from trading with the US.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Spain and the Dutch Republic were invited to join by both France and the United States in the treaty, but neither was responsive to the request.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On June 13, 1778, France declared war on Great Britain, and it invoked the French military alliance with the US, which ensured additional US private support for French possessions in the Caribbean.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with the soldiers and navy that France would send to America, primarily through Lafayette on his staff.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] French assistance made critical contributions required to defeat Cornwallis at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British military had considerable experience fighting in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, in previous conflicts they benefited from local logistics and support from the colonial militia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In the American Revolutionary War, reinforcements had to come from Europe, and maintaining large armies over such distances was extremely complex; ships could take three months to cross the Atlantic, and orders from London were often outdated by the time they arrived.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Prior to the conflict, the colonies were largely autonomous economic and political entities, with no centralized area of ultimate strategic importance.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This meant that, unlike Europe where the fall of a capital city often ended wars, that in America continued even after the loss of major settlements such as Philadelphia, the seat of Congress, New York, and Charleston.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British power was reliant on the Royal Navy, whose dominance allowed them to resupply their own expeditionary forces while preventing access to enemy ports.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, the majority of the American population was agrarian, rather than urban; supported by the French navy and blockade runners based in the Dutch Caribbean, their economy was able to survive.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Lord North, Prime Minister since 1770, delegated control of the war in North America to Lord George Germain and the Earl of Sandwich, who was head of the Royal Navy from 1771 to 1782.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Defeat at Saratoga in 1777 made it clear the revolt would not be easily suppressed, especially after the Franco-American alliance of February 1778.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] With Spain also expected to join the conflict, the Royal Navy needed to prioritize either the war in America or in Europe; Germain advocated the former, Sandwich the latter.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] North initially backed the Southern strategy attempting to exploit divisions between the mercantile north and slave-owning south, but after the defeat of Yorktown, he was forced to accept that this policy had failed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It was clear the war was lost, although the Royal Navy forced the French to relocate their fleet to the Caribbean in November 1781 and resumed a close blockade of American trade.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The resulting economic damage and rising inflation meant the US was now eager to end the war, while France was unable to provide further loans; Congress could no longer pay its soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The geographical size of the colonies and limited manpower meant the British could not simultaneously conduct military operations and occupy territory without local support.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Debate persists over whether their defeat was inevitable; one British statesman described it as "like trying to conquer a map".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Ferling argues Patriot victory was nothing short of a miracle, Ellis suggests the odds always favored the Americans, especially after Howe squandered the chance of a decisive British success in 1776, an "opportunity that would never come again".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The US military history speculates the additional commitment of 10,000 fresh troops in 1780 would have placed British victory "within the realm of possibility".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The expulsion of France from North America in 1763 led to a drastic reduction in British troop levels in the colonies; in 1775, there were only 8,500 regular soldiers among a civilian population of 2.8 million.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The bulk of military resources in the Americas were focused on defending sugar islands in the Caribbean; Jamaica alone generated more revenue than all thirteen American colonies combined.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] With the end of the Seven Years' War, the permanent army in Britain was also cut back, which resulted in administrative difficulties when the war began a decade later.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over the course of the war, there were four separate British commanders-in-chief.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first was Thomas Gage, appointed in 1763, whose initial focus was establishing British rule in former French areas of Canada.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many in London blamed the revolt on his failure to take firm action earlier, and he was relieved after the heavy losses incurred at the Battle of Bunker Hill.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] His replacement was Sir William Howe, a member of the Whig faction in Parliament who opposed the policy of coercion advocated by Lord North; Cornwallis, who later surrendered at Yorktown, was one of many senior officers who initially refused to serve in North America.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The 1775 campaign showed the British overestimated the capabilities of their own troops and underestimated the colonial militia, requiring a reassessment of tactics and strategy, and allowing the Patriots to take the initiative.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Howe's responsibility is still debated; despite receiving large numbers of reinforcements, Bunker Hill seems to have permanently affected his self-confidence and lack of tactical flexibility meant he often failed to follow up opportunities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many of his decisions were attributed to supply problems, such as his failure to pursue Washington's beaten army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Having lost the confidence of his subordinates, he was recalled after Burgoyne surrendered at Saratoga.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Following the failure of the Carlisle Commission, British policy changed from treating the Patriots as subjects who needed to be reconciled to enemies who had to be defeated.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In 1778, Howe was replaced by Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Regarded as an expert on tactics and strategy, like his predecessors Clinton was handicapped by chronic supply issues.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In addition, Clinton's strategy was compromised by conflict with political superiors in London and his colleagues in North America, especially Admiral Mariot Arbuthnot, replaced in early 1781 by Rodney.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] He was neither notified nor consulted when Germain approved Cornwallis's invasion of the south in 1781 and delayed sending him reinforcements believing the bulk of Washington's army was still outside New York City.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the surrender at Yorktown, Clinton was relieved by Carleton, whose major task was to oversee the evacuation of Loyalists and British troops from Savannah, Charleston, and New York City.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] During the 18th century, states commonly hired foreign soldiers, including Britain.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When it became clear additional troops were needed to suppress the revolt in America, it was decided to employ professional German soldiers.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] There were several reasons for this, including public sympathy for the Patriot cause, a historical reluctance to expand the British army and the time needed to recruit and train new regiments.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many smaller states in the Holy Roman Empire had a long tradition of renting their armies to the highest bidder.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The most important was Hesse-Kassel, known as "the Mercenary State".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first supply agreements were signed by the North administration in late 1775; 30,000 Germans served in the American War.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Often generically referred to as "Hessians", they included men from many other states, including Hanover and Brunswick.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Sir Henry Clinton recommended recruiting Russian troops whom he rated very highly, having seen them in action against the Ottomans; however, negotiations with Catherine the Great made little progress.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Unlike previous wars their use led to intense political debate in Britain, France, and even Germany, where Frederick the Great refused to provide passage through his territories for troops hired for the American war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In March 1776, the agreements were challenged in Parliament by Whigs who objected to "coercion" in general, and the use of foreign soldiers to subdue "British subjects".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The debates were covered in detail by American newspapers; in May 1776 they received copies of the treaties themselves, provided by British sympathizers and smuggled into North America from London.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The prospect of foreign German soldiers being used in the colonies bolstered support for independence, more so than taxation and other acts combined; the King was accused of declaring war on his own subjects, leading to the idea there were now two separate governments.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] By apparently showing Britain was determined to go to war, it made hopes of reconciliation seem naive and hopeless, while the employment of what was regarded as "foreign mercenaries" became one of the charges levelled against George III in the Declaration of Independence.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Hessian reputation within Germany for brutality also increased support for the Patriot cause among German American immigrants.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The presence of over 150,000 German Americans meant both sides felt the German soldiers might be persuaded to desert; one reason Clinton suggested employing Russians was that he felt they were less likely to defect.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the first German troops arrived on Staten Island in August 1776, Congress approved the printing of handbills, promising land and citizenship to any willing to join the Patriot cause.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British launched a counter-campaign claiming deserters could be executed.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Desertion among the Germans occurred throughout the war, with the highest rate of desertion occurring between the surrender at Yorktown and the Treaty of Paris.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] German regiments were central to the British war effort; of the estimated 30,000 sent to America, some 13,000 became casualties.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Wealthy Loyalists convinced the British government that most of the colonists were sympathetic toward the Crown; consequently, British military planners relied on recruiting Loyalists, but had trouble recruiting sufficient numbers as the Patriots had widespread support.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Approximately 25,000 Loyalists fought for the British throughout the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although Loyalists constituted about twenty percent of the colonial population, they were concentrated in distinct communities.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many of them lived among large plantation owners in the Tidewater region and South Carolina.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the British began probing the backcountry in 1777–1778, they were faced with a major problem: any significant level of organized Loyalist activity required a continued presence of British regulars.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The available manpower that the British had in America was insufficient to protect Loyalist territory and counter American offensives.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Loyalist militias in the South were constantly defeated by neighboring Patriot militia.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Patriot victory at the Battle of Kings Mountain irreversibly impaired Loyalist militia capability in the South.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the early war policy was administered by Howe, the Crown's need to maintain Loyalist support prevented it from using the traditional revolt suppression methods.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British cause suffered when their troops ransacked local homes during an aborted attack on Charleston in 1779 that enraged both Patriots and Loyalists.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After Congress rejected the Carlisle Peace Commission in 1778 and Westminster turned to "hard war" during Clinton's command, neutral colonists in the Carolinas often allied with the Patriots.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Conversely, Loyalists gained support when Patriots intimidated suspected Tories by destroying property or tarring and feathering.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A Loyalist militia unit—the British Legion—provided some of the best troops in British service.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It was commanded by Tarleton and gained a fearsome reputation in the colonies for "brutality and needless slaughter".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women played various roles during the Revolutionary War; they often accompanied their husbands when permitted.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] For example, throughout the war Martha Washington was known to visit and provide aid to her husband George at various American camps.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women often accompanied armies as camp followers to sell goods and perform necessary tasks in hospitals and camps, and numbered in the thousands during the war.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women also assumed military roles: some dressed as men to directly support combat, fight, or act as spies on both sides.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Anna Maria Lane joined her husband in the Army.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Virginia General Assembly later cited her bravery: she fought while dressed as a man and "performed extraordinary military services, and received a severe wound at the battle of Germantown ... with the courage of a soldier".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On April 26, 1777, Sybil Ludington is said to have ridden to alert militia forces to the British's approach; she has been called the "female Paul Revere".
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Whether the ride occurred is questioned.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A few others disguised themselves as men.
[src:theodorick-bland-congressman/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Deborah Sampson fought until her gender was discovered and she was discharged as a result; Sally St.
